WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
I'm good.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Okay.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
We're rolling.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Okay. So today is Saturday, April 13th, where Malibu, California, and this is David Cline on behalf of the Southern Oral History Program.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:28.000
And the Smithsonian Institutes National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
And today I will be the interviewer.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
I'm with John Bishop, the videographer, and Willie Leventhal.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
And Willie wanted to thank you very much for being part of our project.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:40.000
You know, it's a good story.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
The whole of this, the Pacific Ocean is behind this, well, well.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.000
It's a great honor.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:51.000
And I think that, you know, this was a key part of American history and world history.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
And there are so many lessons for the world to know about how you try and change things without violence.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And so I'm more than happy to be a part of this.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Thank you so much.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:15.000
So, Will, I wanted, if I could ask you to start just by telling us about where you grew up and how you grew up and how you may have seen some of the lessons that you learned early on playing out in the work that you chose.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Born in New York in 46, but my dad had just gotten back from World War II.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:29.000
He had a very good chiropractic practice in Saginaw, Michigan when he went in the war.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:37.000
My mother, who was a teacher and later a college professor at USC, a special ed, went back and lived with her family in Staten Island.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:44.000
And when my dad got out, I had to sort of start over again, you know, after a couple years away for service.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
And, you know, that was when the migration was happening to California.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
And apparently he talked to some people in Michigan and they said, yeah, there's a lot of opportunity out there.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Still being in the service, he could fly free out to California and Bernard, Dr. Bernard Leventhal' name.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
They were both my parents, remember, as an NAACP at different times.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.000
I don't know at that time, but I know that Hubert Humphrey was his big hero from 1948.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
In fact, when I worked for George McGovern, took here in 1972 and we got the nomination over Hubert Humphrey.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:23.000
It took many decades for my father to forgive me for working against Hubert Humphrey, who was his hero of his generation as many like Jackie Robinson, Amart, Luther King, and John Kennedy, for my generation.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:31.000
So we moved to New York to California. When I was two, we didn't have much to start with out here.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.000
So we lived in Ramona Gardens, which was a federal housing project, probably about 1948.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:46.000
My mother worked in the campaign of the first Hispanic councilman and then later congressmen.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
But I'm blanking on his name. The federal building is named for him downtown. I'll think of it later.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Roybal, Edward R. Roybal. Since we become friends with somebody at Cal State LA, did a book about Edward R. Roybal.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:05.000
My sister had talked to Edward R. Roybal before he died. His daughter, Lucille Roybal-Allard, has his seat.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
He remembered my mother. My mother was an activist.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:18.000
And my grandfather had been the assistant superintendent of New York City Schools, Morris Segal, and had handled all the veterans retreating and all the vocational education after World War II.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:28.000
So I come from a family of educators on my mom's side. My dad were also immigrants. His father and mother were immigrants as my grandparents on both sides.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And they had shoe stores. They had shoe stores. And then the typical next generation became a college educated.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
My dad was the only one of his generation to be college educated.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:50.000
So we lived in the projects for a couple of years. And I think that shaped me in the sense I saw pictures in the book you have of Hispanic kids, Asian kids, black kids, all living in that.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:58.000
In fact, the picture from the LA weekly, I could have had that picture taken anywhere when they chose me as a person of the year after I went to the White House for the Civil Rights Concert.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And I particularly went back to Murchison Street Elementary School, which is right up the street from the projects.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:09.000
When my brother and sister went and I substitute taught when I worked in LA here, Steve for five years. And so those are my roots East LA, East Los.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:18.000
So I'm culturally, I think mostly Jewish, but a good bit Hispanic and black, particularly the food for both of those cultures.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:26.000
But anyway, so we then moved to North Hollywood. My dad first built in some of his veterans' buddies from the Jewish War veterans.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:34.000
They built a little front to the house we bought. And that was his waiting room. And he used to do his adjustments in the living room.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:40.000
And then he made a little more success in him and one guy built about an eight room office in front of our house.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:51.000
My parents then divorced. And I moved with my mom. She was a special ed teacher in the public schools and like the county public special ed program better than the city.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And so we ended up in the first in Westchester and then in the South Bay area. And I think Westchester was a very key event in my life.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Beyond my family's commitment to quote unquote liberal of that day, which was a very close bond between Jews and blacks and the NAACP Legal Defense Fund with Jack Greenberg and others worked with Thurgood Marshall.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And my grandfather, as I said in an article, I had donated money to the defense of the Scottsboro Boys. The parents were part of the NAACP, you know, as far as membership.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:42.000
My father, as I said, loved you were done free. But when I was a little baseball player at age 10, most of the kids were Catholic. And they never directed the word kike to me personally, but they used it as a kind of a slang negative word you kike you this.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I'm going to do you down that that was also very prevalent in South Bay. Only three Jewish families in my high school. Again, never directed at me and me really not knowing what to make of it, but very painful to a child.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:03.000
Because of course as a child, you want to fit in, you want to you don't want people. And of course I didn't understand why they would even say that about my religion.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:19.000
Because I like my parents and the people I met at Temple, they didn't do anything wrong that I knew of. And of course at that time within the Catholic Church, there was the, which later changed and it's a whole different day in the Catholic Church in terms of relations with Israel and Judaism.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And Judaism, in those days, there was the Christ killer that was at that particular for a certain time. So came out and then the next thing that happened, which is tremendously connected to the word kike, was the Jackie Robinson movie, Jackie Robinson story, which I saw at age five.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And here on the screen, there were two things that I related to, baseball, which I love, still love. And racial prejudice or prejudice towards somebody and mistreatment of somebody more verbally with Robinson in that movie than otherwise.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And in the Jack Robinson movie, which came out this weekend, there was a great scene with Harrison Ford, Willie Terrells, the Jack Robinson actor. I was just there and there's a little white boy who was imitating you. And I talked to Andrew Young about the movie and Andy said, the movie was great best civil rights move I've ever saw. And he said, I thought of you when I saw the movie thinking of me.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And he may have thought, I've been trying to get Jackie's teammates involved with the civil rights game. I was one that got Andrew Young involved through my RBI involvement went with him to Cincinnati when he gave the address there at the civil rights game in 2009 or 10.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:43.000
And I didn't identify with Jackie as a ball player. First of all, he was such he was probably the best athlete in the country for many years, maybe of all time. Him and Jim Thorpe were close, but Jackie was unbelievable athlete.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:08:11.000
(Jackie Robinson) projected to be in the 1940 Olympics like it was a brother Mac, but they had no Olympics that year. Would I identified with Jackie Robinson? I always tried to describe it as, whoa, because by that time Willie Willie Mays around blacks or plan. You don't hear of any. I didn't know anything about this. I was 10 years old. I just knew the blacks were in the big leagues. They were my heroes somewhere on Brooklyn Dodgers. That's all I knew. And I remember the way I described it as in my 10 year old mind, it was my the grownups didn't tell me about this.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:31.000
They didn't tell me about any of this. The blacks and whites couldn't play baseball. I want to find out more about this. I want to find out about this. They really picked my my curiosity. And I wanted to be like Jackie Robinson not as a player because I didn't think that much at that time when I eventually learned about Jackie Robinson. I knew I wasn't going to be Jackie Robinson.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And no one else was going to be Jackie Robinson by the way either, but I couldn't run fast and Jackie could certainly run fast. But he was a healer. What Jackie did, what impressed me in that film was he challenged the people that were saying mean things and hurting people's feelings. And he made it better. And he helped people whose feelings were hurt. And his feelings were hurt, but he was tough enough strong enough courageous enough dedicated enough, you know, an exceptional enough athlete to over the world.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:19.000
And that was what fascinated me. And that's what he became a hero for. Not that he could play baseball, that he could be that he could heal this terrible hurt that I felt not to the extent that he felt or that African Americans felt, but it was still a pain. It was still a confusion to me.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:35.000
My mother was smart enough when I was I didn't get by Mitzett mainly because I wanted to play baseball on Saturday when the religious school was all my friends were playing baseball. And I don't want to take that much time out to go to the religious school because I've been Mr. Many Games with my mom let me get away with after the divorce.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:43.000
My dad didn't care. He was a secular teacher. He didn't go after World War II. He said, you know, I don't believe in God after all, you know, that he was a secular teacher to identify with Israel.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:10:04.000
My mother wanted me to have a Jewish education. My grandfather, Seagull, really wanted me to have one. When I got 15, she said, you must be confirmed. And I fought it, but she forced me, one of the first things she ever forced me to do. And then I embraced it. All the other Jewish kids were just getting done with it. They were couldn't wait to get done. And I discovered it. And one of my buddies in the confirmation class was a guy named Mike Vogel turned out to be first to be a student.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:11.000
Turned out to be first team All City in football and baseball at Westchester High where I would have gone had I not moved.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:20.000
Played us. Played was second team All American at Northridge football full back. I played baseball. I don't know if he was All America. And then played some pro football.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Another one of the non-Woodie Allen-esque Jews who were athletes in strong and macho. And I love Woody Allen for his talent.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Not for his representation of the Jewish male because some of us are not nebish little wimps, no disrespect to Woody Allen. But we like to think of ourselves as very good athletes who competed, whose role models were Hank Greenberg, Sandy Koufax, Al Rosen, who was a boxer.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And I had a chance to meet Al Rosen and Sandy Koufax and interview Sandy Koufax. And spend some time with Al Rosen when he was out with Ted Williams in Iowa.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:09.000
You know the Jewish community needs to recognize there's a stream that runs from Hank and Al and Sandy through Mike Vogel, who was much better than me.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:18.000
But I was good enough to be on one of the best teams in the state. And lots of Jews are that good. Mike's safe for UCLA and his three sons who were professional athletes.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:28.000
I just name a few. And that's my challenge to my own culture. When Snick said go work in your own community, I got a lot of work to do in the Jewish community.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Still, then and now. That more now. So you asked about my early years. But the early years were influenced by my family, by the divorce coming from a broken home with Jackie Robinson also didn't have a fall.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:53.000
I mean, there was a lot of things that I could identify with Jackie Robinson. And then I went up to UCLA. And the other big influence that that early part of my life was John Kennedy.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:12:06.000
He was so charismatic. He was a good looking PT-109. He was a World War II hero. I mean, you couldn't have been much more heroic for me at that age than torn somebody through the water and these things. He was also very funny.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:17.000
He gave such a great speech. We're coming up to the anniversary in June. The night before Medgar Evers was killed about the issue being as old as the scriptures and as current as our Constitution.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:30.000
And you know Eisenhower was a grandfather figure to my generation. Kennedy was the new frontier. And also, of course, they asked not what your country can do for you, but what you can do for your country. That resonated. I was.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:44.000
Had I not gone south, I would have been attracted towards the Peace Corps, but I went. Dr. King found me before the Peace Corps found me. But I was very, you know, that was a great thing that for my generation in terms of idealism.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:59.000
So those were really, and then that was very primed. And then of course, when I was 12, Brooklyn Dodgers came out. They had three Jews on the team. They had Sandy Koufax, Norm Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry + Norm Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry and Norm Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry. And what a great deal. By 59, Sandy was just coming into his own. And Norm Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry + Norm Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry + Norm Sherry + Larry Sherry was the World Series MVP.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:08.000
One two games, save two games. So as a Jewish kid, that was thrilling. And I actually got to work out with Brooklyn Dodgers three times when I was 13 and 14.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:15.000
At the Colosseum on the floor, Pete Reiser kind of adopted me. And Gil Hodges as well gets sitting the bench with him. So that was pretty neat.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:22.000
So I had a lot of great things with my childhood. And then Dr. King came to UCLA when I was 18 and asked for volunteers.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:32.000
And now the summer community organization and political education project, which was known as scope, SCOPE project, and made the National Nelson at UCLA.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:40.000
I'm quite sure because of Ralph Bunche and Jackie Robinson, each of whom had been on the front lines with him every year from 60 through 65.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:41.000
One or the other.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.000
How aware of the civil rights movement or King were you before he came to UCLA?

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
Actually, my, and I'm, I'm, this is 65.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:55.000
Yeah, I'm going to name drop because Harris Wofford and I are good friends along with Andy. I'm those are my two big, big name friends of mine.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Some, but wonderful men. And Harris and I, Harris was just in Birmingham with Almopile and Diane McWhorter. And, and he mentioned, I said, well, I'm maybe I'll be back in DC, the anniversary of the March in Washington.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
And he said, were you there? And I said, well, no, I wasn't yet 17. I was getting ready for high school football and I had my own column in the Valley News and Greensheet.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:22.000
I was only kid that had his own column and covered B football. And then when I got to play varsity, they sent her her crop.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:29.000
And I remember the name photographer over with the orders, only take pictures of Willie Leventhal. And of course, he took six pictures. All of me in one was in the paper the next day.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:32.000
So I was very happy. The little bit I got to play, at least I got in the paper.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:40.000
So, we went to the City Finals, which was on TV and I was coaching third bass instead of playing, which was extremely disappointing.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:49.000
But we were in the City Finals and that was for those days, it was a big deal. There was no divisions. It was one tournament, one out of all the City of LA and two teams made it.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:57.000
And in Birmingham, we had beat him five times in a row and they beat us. And my teammates never kind of forgave themselves for losing that game.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So those influences were going on. And I was what I said about Tahris. I was aware of the March in Washington, but I was in California, I was 16.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:22.000
I was trying to get some playing time in football. I was little and not very big. I was in a new school. I just been there three quarters of my junior year, going in my senior year.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:37.000
But I knew what was going on. And also the three guys that were killed in Mississippi to a re-Jewish that same summer, or the summer before, next summer, when I was a senior, my senior summer, that had a big impact on me.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:46.000
The first time I really remember, as I told Harris, and the March in Washington, Jackie Robinson was far more the influence of my life than Martin Luther King.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:16:03.000
Twenty months later, Dr. King came and wanted to ask for volunteers. But I remember very clearly being aware enough, Dr. King went into Selma January 1st at the request of many of the educators. Some of the snake people will say that they did all the work and Dr. King came and took the credit.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:16.000
There was a group of educators and town leaders. And the way Andy and Hosea Williams tell about it, snicked a great work in Selma. But they were beaten down. The repression was terrible. The violence was terrible.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:23.000
And unfortunately, the media didn't cover enough. The Justice Department didn't do enough. And they suffered a lot of losses as they had in Mississippi.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:36.000
But the fact was, they were being beaten down. And we didn't need the media there. And those leaders in the town, and they were very easy to research and find out (Mrs. Amelia) Boynton was certainly one of them.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:51.000
And there were some others in the school system. Requested Dr. King and SCLC came in. And I remember the article in the paper, January 2nd, I remember, so, well, I had a girlfriend up in Big Sur that I was trying to commute back and forth from UCLA, which was quite difficult.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:17:04.000
But her father was a Navy veteran. He was in the hospital. He had a drinking problem. And he was critical of Dr. King. And he was trying to tell me, well, the service that didn't work and the black need grows for this and that. And I said, you know what? This is about voting.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:14.000
I said, I don't care what you're talking about. This is a democracy. They're trying to register to vote. You're not going to persuade me that he's doing something wrong.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:30.000
So I had that conversation with my girlfriend, stepfather. And I mean, I have noticed it in the paper anyway. And I think I was, again, the 60 killings in 64 and Freedom Summer. But that was my first time I can personally now remember knowing what Martin Luther King was doing.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:43.000
It was news when he went into Selma. And then I followed that. Of course, it was big news. And it was the the Selma-to-Montgomery marches, you know, the Selma-to-Montgomery marches. I think it was the Selma-to-Montgomery marches.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:53.000
There was the Selma-to-Montgomery marches. They call it the Selma-to-Montgomery marches. And you know, little did I know that Hosea Williams would become one of my dearest, dearest closest friends. I would have, at this point, the only book about him.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:05.000
He's got a manuscript that he flew me down for to work on him. And he would, we were, we're going to go to Savannah. We're going to go down to out of Pogless. Then we'd be in the office and a poor person would come. And he didn't interrupt our work and go counsel the poor person.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:16.000
And which is a wonderful thing about him because he had the poor people's church of love. Martin Luther King, poor people, church of love at the time. He had a storefront on Pstri and a young had an office on the 45th floor almost across the street.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:25.000
But he, that manuscript is still sitting with his family that we were going to do. So my book was the only one. But he led that March on the Selma-to-Montgomery marches with John R. Lewis.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:40.000
And Dr. King came month and a half later to UCLA. And had I not gone, I don't think I would have gone south. But Dr. King was so impressive that I was ready to go, but still afraid.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And it took actually a friend to confront me, another Jewish friend from, I played football with at high school. And he was going and he said, why don't you come. And I had no excuse except I'm scared, which I was.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:19:07.000
I was waiting to be a counselor in a prison, but I'd gotten the thing saying you're too young. You can't be a counselor in a prison until you're 21. But I had been interested in, in being a social worker at that time in my life. Just sort of what I did in my life anyway.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:17.000
And so Dr. King made a, made an appeal at UCLA made the national announcement. And they had a Joel Siegel was one of the Rick key organizers, Richard "Rick" Tuttle, another key organizer.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:27.000
Even if he didn't want to talk about it in your interview, but, but and he was actually our advisor. He was our, you know, he was an old man of 25 at that time. We were all 18 and 19 and 20.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:41.000
And Rick was kind of our on campus advisor. In fact, when I was arrested in America with John R. Lewis and others of the UCLA group were with us, the pictures are in the book, front page news. I have the video from CBS NBC, ABC, which Joel got me.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:49.000
Rick actually was connected enough politically at that time to get to Glenn M. Anderson, who was Lieutenant Governor for Edmund G. "Pat" Brown, Edmund G. "Pat" Brown was out of the state.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:20:12.000
And, and Glenn M. Anderson telegramed Carl Sanders and said, we have five UCLA students missing in Americus. Because in those days when you, when you got arrested, like the guys in Mississippi, you didn't know whether you were going to go out in the country. In fact, my first arrest in Americus, I was the happiest civil rights worker when they toured towards the jail and not towards the country. That, that's why that was my, I wasn't so worried about getting arrested. I was worried that I might not go to jail.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:35.000
And so Rick, Rick did that. There was one point of telegram with my name and the other's names that Rick arranged. So Rick was very involved with scope, disturbing divine worship. I went two weeks. I went first, first week, just me and John, maybe there's some other people behind me and John were in front. And the fire chief was actually quite an interesting experience. I've told him many times.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:21:00.000
I went to Americus from Macon, Hosea Williams wanted people to go down to see a hot movement. And I think because of my athletic background and being little, I had to, you know, they talk about giving 110%. When you're five, eight hundred and forty pounds, most of the guys are six feet and bigger. If you look at my teams, I'm always one of the smaller ones, although in high school, it was kind of a small team, although we had, you know, let's say half of us were small comparatively to the guys over six feet.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:27.000
You work harder. You have to work harder or you can't compete. And I wasn't as gifted. I was good enough to be with the most gifted in LA, but at the bottom of the group. And the only reason I was with the most gifted and when I say most gifted, there's a Steve Sogge who played quarterback at USC. And then for Brooklyn Dodgers, Jeff Pentland + Tom Griffin, who was on my team, who played 12 years in the big league, Jeff Pentland + Jeff Pentland + Tom Griffin, who was in the Hall of Famine, Arizona State was a semi-social sitting coach with the, getting coach for Brooklyn Dodgers now with Seattle.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:41.000
I mean, there's a difference. Those guys end up in the big leagues and in the Hall of Fame. Guys like me, if we work real hard, we can compete with them. And so I wasn't that gift. I was good. I mean, some guys don't make the team. I made the team. So I was good enough to do that.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:50.000
But so I was at the bottom run of the best in LA, which is good. So I could play when I integrated the making bombers and that league and making.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:22:08.000
So what we were talking about is, is the UCLA thing. So Dr. King came, are we back on? So Dr. King came. Joel Siegel really was taking the lead, raised some money. Dr. King had a lunch at URC, University of Religious Conference.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:11.000
And for people who don't know if Tanya tells you Joel Siegel is?

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:26.000
Joel Siegel at that time was the humor editor of the Daily Bruin and was in Calps, which is a spirit organization. And as he said, I later became Joel Siegel, I'm good morning America entertainment editor.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:37.000
And if you did one piece in Israel as well, he did some, he did a little other journalism, but mainly he's known for entertainment and movie reviews, which he was very successful at. Very well loved that.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:47.000
He came over to Queens College when I published this book. We did a program there. UCLA has never done a program for my book. Joel would have flown out for one. They refused.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:23:01.000
But weren't interested. What interested for six years in doing even a plaque for Dr. King and only did it because they were ordered to Queens College in braces. That's where Andy Goodman went to school. That's one of, one that was killed with James, James, Cheney and Mickey Schwerner.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:16.000
So Dr. King, I remember there were two things in a speech. I'd be happy to tell you that really impressed me when I listened to it. I hadn't, again, not yet decided. I would volunteer, but wanted to and felt it was the right thing to do.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:35.000
You want to know the two things that impressed me. One thing he talked about the three versions of love in Greek, a Goppy Filia and an Aros as a teenager with hormones. I was very familiar with the Aros, but the Goppy and Filia were totally new concepts to me.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:56.000
And very interesting topics that you could divide love in the other things because at that point, Aros is pretty overwhelming when you're 18. The hormones were there. And of course, I loved my family and I had friends that were women that I didn't think of in sexual ways, but that was a pretty macho playboy time culture for young males in America.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:12.000
So that was very interesting to me. And also it was a way of understanding and putting into a theoretical context why I was interested and upset that people were being mistreated because they weren't showing a Goppy or Filia.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:21.000
And that was what supposedly America was about. Land of the free home of the brave out of many one. What could be more Filia and a Goppy than that.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:35.000
So the other thing was he had a great sense of humor because Dr. King about halfway through his speech, he was talking about the history, many of the good things that had happened. And he said, I could stop here.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:44.000
He said, but first of all, Baptist preachers don't give short sermons and everybody laughed, of course. And he said, but I need to tell you the other part too that there's a lot more work to do.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:25:05.000
And he was just a likable guy. Carrot, not he wasn't giving the kind of oration that he gave in the March. I mean, I have the tape that I got before. I think it's now restricted. I don't think he could get it from audiovisual UCLA. But before then I did get a copy. And actually I provided UCLA with a transcript that I paid for without any thanks.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:21.000
But he was he was a person. And of course, Franklin Murphy introduced him and he said, this is I think when legend meets reality. And he said, this is the moral leader of our country.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:37.000
Franklin Murphy was taking somewhat of a risk because the FBI was going around every place that invited Dr. King and trying to sabotage it. And I mean, because I wrote the report to President Reagan and the Congress on the first King holiday for Coretta Scott King. And I read all the congressional testimony.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:47.000
And since researching David J. Garrow's slimy, sleazy book using Hoover's Files, which Taylor Branch also does. And I think a very disreputable way.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:59.000
Have researched much of this from the 19 volumes that are at the UCLA Library of the House Assassinations Commission report, who they start out that report by saying we hesitate to include many of these files.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:14.000
But so the reader has an understanding we are including them, but we are cautioning the reader that these represent a shameful chapter in American history. And these are unverified attributions towards people's personal lives and political affiliations.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:28.000
Which is never found in Taylor Branch's book or David J. Garrow's book after they heavily quote those same files. They quote the same files that the Congress investigated with hundreds of thousands of dollars over many years, produced a report 19 volumes.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:44.000
But then they and in my book that that's some part of is in that book went to Cass Canfield in Harper and Row. And he wanted it, but he wanted me to put sex things in just as Holt, Rinehart and Winston did just as many New York publishers want to sell books.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:56.000
I said no. Taylor Branch David J. Garrow said yes. They won Pulitzer Prizes. I did. I was on Tony Brown and he said this is after Gierro's book. He said Mr. Leventhal, you're challenging the Pulitzer Prize.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:08.000
Some people may say you're jealous of David J. Garrow because he won it and you didn't. I was a little caught off guard because Tony Brown and I had actually arranged which he didn't want me to say on camera, but he had worked with me a little bit on the background of our interview.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:16.000
But it was still a challenge to go on national TV and be talking about Dr. King's personal life at all because it's not something that anybody's business in my opinion.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:29.000
But I said well, but I wasn't expecting that question. I said well you know I would be just honest if I said I wouldn't have loved or wouldn't love to win a Pulitzer Prize for a book I did on Dr. King, but I would not want a Pulitzer Prize for that book.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:37.000
I would not want anything to do with that book. A Pulitzer Prize is not more important to me than telling the truth and not using these kinds of files.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:28:00.000
So, but anyway that's a long answer to that visit by Dr. King. There was a committee set up. Joel again was very involved. Richard "Rick" Tuttle, I'm sure Rick me had mentioned Alex White to you. I don't know if he did, but Alex White who's not in good health now was ran the service organization at UCLA to send people to internships.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:11.000
Alex was involved at the time and I was just a freshman and of course my excuse to myself was when I was not going to do it because I was afraid I was like oh I'm just a freshman.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:20.000
I kept thinking of reasons they've got a lot of people I'm sure I'm just a freshman. They got better people than me when the real wasn't going to go down there. They're going to kill me just like they did the guys last summer.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:37.000
But when my friend confronted me I just had that decision and that was my whole life up till then. Hearing the kite words Jackie Robinson, you know the March on Washington, some black friends I had.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:55.000
I did write what I told Harris Wofford, I did write an editorial or only sports for my high school paper except two articles. One was about cigarette smoking because my mom had already had an operation for lung cancer and she died three years later from lung cancer and the stress of me being in the movement I think was not particularly good for her.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:03.000
I was very personal experience for me in that sense that I put stress on my family by making the decision to get involved and stay involved.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:17.000
My dad was very happy that I went he wasn't that bad I stayed involved after I came back after three arrests and so on. Because he said you've done your part. You served your tour you don't have to keep doing this and I said well they've asked me to be the college coordinator.

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:31.000
I was very involved I think it was a very religious thing for me as well. I think I found a real religious connection to my Judaism and the Judaism was a big connection to the explanation of how to respond to anti-Semitism.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:43.000
Can I ask you to talk a little bit more about that first thing because I often feel that people's civil rights experiences are very much like a conversion experience.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:47.000
What they experience there and how they relate to it.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:30:07.000
I wanted to finish there was one other one I mean what I'll eventually wander back to it later but not so much of a conversion that there's a letter in that book that I was it was a letter I wrote to my then roommate Charlie Goldberg who he took it to the day of broom and they published it.

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:20.000
And I've actually heard it from some of the other people that were in the scope project. I had not been around a lot of black people only two were in my high school I played baseball and football against the kids from San Fernando,

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:30.000
Pacoima were Mexican and black at that time. And so I didn't have a lot of personal experience. The editorial in the high school paper I do want to talk about that first.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:43.000
That came about because Grant at that time was a very TV Hollywood kind of place. Tom Selleck there for good basketball player track guy. James Keach + James Keach + Stacy Keach was a good friend of mine.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:51.000
I was up the road here. I was married to Jane Seymour, Dr. Quinn. James did a great movie about Johnny Cash and the long writers with his brother Stacy.

00:30:51.000 --> 00:31:00.000
Many other Hollywood people one of whom was a guy named Kim Weiskopf who's dad wrote I love Lucy. Kim being well to do went to a Beverly Hills camp.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:06.000
One of the counselors was a black guy who went to Cal State LA was all American football player Cal State when they still had football team.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:14.000
I went to a party one that summer my junior summer with Kim and this African American and those age would have said Degro guy was there.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:27.000
Nice guy in the world. Great singer. He sang at the party. I got a meeting. Nice guy in the world. Then Proposition 14 was on the ballot in 64 which was the anti discrimination housing thing which which loss by the way and the Rumford Fair Housing Act.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:40.000
It's got then declared I believe unconstitutional. The other editorial beside smoking was about this African American young man who I named at the time. I don't remember his name anymore. It's still in the grand odyssey files.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:50.000
I was with my friend Kim Weiskopf who was the photographer for the paper later went in and wrote good times and created a full house. 9 to 5 married with children.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:59.000
I died recently not too long with cancer sadly but had a great career in Hollywood. Followed his father. Norman Lear got him his first job. Nice when you get your father's friends and Norman Lear.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:12.000
Kim took me to the party and I said I was at a party with Kim. I met this guy. He's a great guy. He's an all-American football player. He's a great student. He sings great. I said but some people went to him for a neighbor because he's Negro.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:28.000
I was mature enough at 17 to say I think it was one of the better things I've ever written. I told Harris I said I think I was with the march on Washington in spirit. I was mature enough to write that article based on my friendship with him.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:35.000
The conversion to go back to your question was when we then went to the south there was an immersion into the black community.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:44.000
Those of us who wanted to feel we looked at everybody the same. You can't look at everybody the same if you're only around white people because black people look different.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:53.000
Not better, worse. Just the same thing I would say with gay people. It's not better, worse. It's different. I don't know why we can't just say people can be different.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:33:02.000
That's okay. That doesn't mean we don't like them. It doesn't mean we're homophobic. We just say a marriage between a man and a man and a woman and a woman is different.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:12.000
It doesn't have to be the same. I've always felt, pick a new word. Say it's my loved one. This is my loved one. I mean I think we should change it all.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:28.000
Men and women should say this is my loved one. Take the word marriage away because that offends older conservative people who don't hate people but hate that they're losing what they consider is very sacred for generations and history and blah blah blah what they said at the Supreme Court.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:34.000
I thought the discussion was pretty good. I think we should get away from marriage and that everybody talk about their loved one.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:41.000
Some people's loved ones are their children like Dr. King, a Goppy Philly, an arrows. You can have arrows for the man, arrows for the woman. I don't care.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:50.000
I hate to see all this division and pain about the subject as somebody with this background and people have suggested that get the state out of it.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:59.000
But I think we should have a new word for it. Not marriage, my loved one. My loved one. And just say some things are different.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:15.000
And again it's different when you're not around Black people. The great story is in other people that I've now Sherry LeBetus who's written a new book, another woman who's writing a book, Maria Gitin University Alabama about scope, scope workers after my effort to for organize our first SNCCAS reunion every year.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:24.000
Multiple ones, every 10 years, 50 years. The Attorney General comes to their reunion. I had one reunion. We've only in scope had one ever.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:31.000
There was a professor from Albany, New York who did his group in South Carolina. Andy N came because it was in Atlanta and Andy's my friend. And he's so nice to have come.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:37.000
And that's what I got an article in the United States Constitution. Fox News was going to come but we quit a little too early.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:50.000
But a number of us have said it was so different when we immersed in the Black community. And within a few weeks Black people would just look normal.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:58.000
They weren't different anymore because we saw them every day. And then they didn't all look the same either because they're all different shades.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:05.000
They have different lips, different noses, different, just like white people. We're all different. But with the skin colors, different hues.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:19.000
And in fact, the great story, there's a young man, not anymore, but at the time, who worked from Carlisle, Carlisle, Pennsylvania, forgetting the college.

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:25.000
David said I can't remember the name, but anyway, he had the same experience I did. And he said when he knew it was time to go, he stayed extra like I did.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:35.000
He said, he stayed till November. And he said his mother called him and he thought, why is this white woman calling me? And he said, he said, that's wrong.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:43.000
He said, I knew I needed a break at that time. And I know for me the way I describe it is in the beginning, the Black people look different.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:51.000
By the end of the summer, the White people look different. I didn't think I was Black, but Black people were my friends. Black people were my baseball teammates.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:36:01.000
The white people literally wanted to kill me and did try and kill me. So the white people look different to me. And just within three months, it shows how my background is sociology, it shows how a cultureation.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:10.000
So one of the conversions is that emotionally, and I said in that letter, I used to want and used to believe I wasn't prejudiced since everybody the same.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:16.000
But now I really feel that way because I know Black people. I know more Black people than I used to in those days, Negroes.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:27.000
And so that's one part of the conversion is that when you have so many Black friends and you're living with a Black family, that becomes your life.

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:34.000
And you have no more doubts that you're going to treat people different because they're Black.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:39.000
Because everybody's Black, that you're new. So they become, and then the young, beautiful Black women become young, beautiful women.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:47.000
And the good athletes become good athletes and the color fades to very little significant at that point.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:54.000
So let me just ask you where you went if you could just tell if they could create that.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:37:07.000
Yeah, so the way the scope project was organized, the board of SCLC at Hosea Williams request, and he developed the project, which is in my book, Scope of Freedom, the founding papers, essentially.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:21.000
Proved it in December and they targeted 120 counties. They didn't target. It was much like a battle plan. Hosea Williams was a World War II veteran, was in General George Patton's, what they call the Negro.

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:32.000
Tank Brigade, a great friend of mine, Jim Colaianni, who was a Catholic leader, lay leader, who was at that time executive editor of Ramparts with Jann Wenner.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:39.000
Jann Wenner tried to convince him to go partners with this new magazine that he was going to start. I think it was called Rolling Stone.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:46.000
But Jan was only like 21 and Jim said, yeah, yeah, and that's really cool. But we grownups are doing other stuff.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:52.000
So he didn't, he didn't found Rolling Stone with Jann Wenner. But Jan worked at at Ramparts as a young, young kid.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:38:02.000
But Jim started a business and did sermons, which I think his son is still doing. I think Jim is still alive in New Jersey, it must be in his 80s.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:10.000
He was also a World War II veteran. I did his daughter very briefly, Karen Colaianni Johnson, who I met through somebody in the American campaign,

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:15.000
he had all these connections through politics and civil rights.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:30.000
And the reason I bring up Jim is he did an issue of Ramparts about Selma, and he did it in a military way where he had a joint chiefs of staff almost on the white side, Jim Clark, the black side doctor, King.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:40.000
But he did it as a military battle. And that was very outproposing. And very brilliant. That's the spring issue of Ramparts magazine somewhere in the library.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:50.000
But Hosea Williams really had kind of a battle plan. And the picked 120 counties, which were listed in the book, these were not the worst 120 counties.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:59.000
These were the 120 counties where if they got another 30 or 40% Negro voters, they could knock out the racist and get into moderate.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:10.000
Some of the counties like Lowndes County, Alabama, there was no blacks at all. I mean, you had a longer road. That's why Lowndes County Freedom Organization (LCFO) → Black Panther Party was appropriate in many, many ways and a very good thing in Mississippi and many places.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:21.000
Because you have to move outside the party. Dr. King and scope and Andrew Young, and they wanted to move within the Democratic Party and overturn the worst racist counties.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:29.000
And Andrew Young has told me that those same 120 scope counties all went for Barack Obama and may have made the difference in the election 2008.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:42.000
You can talk to Andy about that, whether I haven't seen those statistics in his congressional, I mean his governor's campaign in Georgia, the scope counties in South Georgia also again were counties that came out heavily for him.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:53.000
Many of those are also worse scope and snickered together. But they wanted 2000 volunteers to man these 120 counties, they only got 500.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:40:01.000
So when people tell you, well, it was all over, it didn't have nothing going on. More people got killed in the year of 65 as civil rights workers than in 64.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:08.000
It was still quite dangerous. I'm sure Cheryl Sharad will verify that and other people from Southwest Georgia.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:15.000
And so, and also at that point, whites were getting killed because blacks were starting to shoot back. That happened in America.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:26.000
Unfortunately, a bystander who was white, who had Andrew Whatley, who I consider a martyr of the movement, who had just joined the Marines, was a bystander when they were throwing rocks at the marchers.

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:37.000
And there was a black car. A car came with two black guys. They weren't part of the movement and they were tired of people being abused and they shot back.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:47.000
I got shot at twice in America because we didn't get to shoot back. That wasn't part of our thing. But there are many snick people that were carrying guns by them.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:58.000
But not, in fact, I tell the story in my article, I think you saw for Benay Muth Magazine, Judson Ford, a Korean War vet. It took a 38 in his belt when we were going out to get kids. We're not in a demonstration now.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:10.000
There was a transition period going through deignants for defense and justice in Louisiana. We're already openly carrying guns. But within the movement, within Dr. King during demonstrations, et cetera, that was our philosophy. And that was a philosophy of scope.

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.000
Did you go through a specific training?

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:23.000
Yeah. But you asked to where I was. Absolutely. The orientation schedule was in there was fascinating. But because we only could get 500, because of the danger, that's why people didn't volunteer.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:31.000
And it was almost all white and not just, you know, there were many blacks in the South. Not too many blacks were coming out of the North to go South. Stoney Cooks was one.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:46.000
And I hope you get a chance to talk to Stony in Washington. But Stony could tell you about that. But Jesse Jackson was another who came into Selma at that time. That was when he got involved with SCLC in Selma. Not in the leadership role, by the way. That came later.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:56.000
But Stony did have a leadership role very quickly. The people with skills and media, there's a lady named Kit Clark, who I just saw about with scope, whose papers are now at the Schomburg.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:05.000
She had some skills. She went to leadership role in scope with Hosea Williams Hosea Williams was good at picking people. He picked me. So I don't know. Hopefully that was a good pick also.

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:15.000
But so we couldn't man the whole 120 counties. We went essentially into 90 counties. They had black leaders in all the 20 counties that had requested people. They were working.

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:21.000
And some of us were shifted around. I worked in two counties primarily, but went into four or five other counties for demonstrations.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:31.000
So that was, they sent out recruiting teams between Selma, between the first of the year, while Selma was going on. They had recruiting teams all around the country, ecologists.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:43.000
And Dr. King himself was the recruiter, UCLA. So I always got to tell people, Dr. King recruited me. Not Hosea Williams, not Andy. I said, Dr. King recruited me. So I don't have to answer to you guys so much as you might want me to.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:49.000
And I think he also knew that I had been picked because I had talked to him personally, got the thinking when they called us in for a meeting.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:43:05.000
But so we went to Atlanta. We were housed at Morehouse College in the dorms. I had, I've recently said I may have learned more and one week at Morse Brown than at six years with a BA and MA, UCLA.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:23.000
Particularly now the way I feel about UCLA and what they've done with the scope history and taking down Dr. King's photo and Franklin Murphy's photo from that wonderful day when Dr. King back to honor by the way, Jackie Robinson and Ralph Butch, who the UCLA people love to make money on and market, particularly Jackie Robinson.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:35.000
And Rachel Robinson does not know this, but I hope to tell her before too. And I just missed her at the civil rights game, sat across from her with Andy and went after the thing that she left early. But I'll see, I'll see Mrs. Robinson at some point.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:41.000
Andy knows, but you know, there's only so many battles you fight at. I mean, this is my battle. I got the plaque up anyway for his visit.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:56.000
But so we have this wonderful orientation. If you're having the book, or I'll tell you who was there at the orientation, it's amazing, amazing. I consider it the best week of education in American history. That's a big statement. Let me tell you who was there. Dr. King spoke to us.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:44:11.000
Bayard Rustin organized A. Philip Randolph, Hosea Williams spoke to us and was at one of the organizers. Norman Hill, who had been at core, was Bayard's assistant. Then we had people like C. Vann Woodward, John Hope Franklin from academia.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:30.000
Lillian Smith was there, didn't speak. We also had Septima Clark, who started the citizenship of education schools. We had Vernon E. Jordan Jr. We had Charles "Chuck" Morgan Jr from, from what the legal organization, ACLU, national leader.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:43.000
We had Clarence M. Mitchell Jr from the end of LACP, the head of the office there. We had the field staff who were in it. We had Michael Harrington, the other America, which was a key book about poverty.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:55.000
We had a number of government people. We had a Jewish man who was head of the meat packers union, whose picture is in there. Why am I forgetting his name? He was there.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:45:07.000
John Doar came down. He's not in the schedule, but he came down and told us how to make reports to him, which Joel Siegel did when my life was threatened, which resulted in 33 gas stations getting desegregated in three states.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:17.000
John Doar had trained us and John Doar ordered J. Edgar Hoover to investigate. Once that happened, the FBI did a very good investigation, which is recorded in my FBI file that's in the book.

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:30.000
It was an extraordinary week. I've forgotten a few people, but just the people I mentioned to you, it's a pretty all-star cast of people to speak to us in a week. Dr. King addressed us.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:45.000
He was a waging thing about Dr. King's speech when he closed with free at last, he said, like in watch and watching, he said Jews and Gentiles, Black and White Protestant cast Jews and Gentiles.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:55.000
When he spoke to us, knowing that there were young people, someone who might be atheists or agnostic, he said Muslims and Hindus and non-believers.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:06.000
Now, here, because he had been to India, he knew about Pakistan and the Muslim and the Hindus fighting there and he knew about Kashmir and I've talked to Kash, and the young has been to Kashmir.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:21.000
He was happy that I even knew about Kashmir because I'm not a global person. But to me, given our world now with the things that are going on the world and the Islamic world, and still with Pakistan and India,

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:36.000
that Dr. King went out of his way to say that and that recording available, by the way, that was at Morehouse College in Jodo, as Chimnasium. Such a far-reaching visionary thing to talk about to a college group.

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:48.000
Now, as we look at it, he was talking about we need to heal these divisions of race and religion, and not just among Jews and Gentiles, among Hindus and Muslims.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:55.000
Although in those days we called, I don't know how those days it was Muslim, but we've changed it to Muslim, but he said Muslim and Hindu.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:47:14.000
And I know the reason he said it was because of Gandhi in India and Pakistan. So it was an amazing week. We're all energized, originally, as with a number of chapters, the gentleman Larry Scott Butler is the one who talked about his mom, and he had a lot of similar experience.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:22.000
He went off to Bogalusa, Louisiana, Louisiana and the man at the house where he stayed had a gun, same thing. He said, my daughter is here because Larry Scott Butler said the same thing.

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:32.000
We're nonviolence. He might be, and the man is going to kill my daughter. And what Andrew Young always said, he said, if it had not been for nonviolence, the South would have been like Northern Ireland.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:41.000
He said, because everybody in the South in rural areas, they all hunt, and most of the people who have been in World War II, and everybody had guns.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:47.000
Yeah, from Korea and World War II. Wasn't that long after World War 15 years after World War II, or 20 years after World War II.

00:47:47.000 --> 00:48:01.000
So if you look at it that way, both SNCC and the NSCLC through nonviolence, you could say they saved the country because if we had been like Northern Ireland at that, that pint in our history with African-Cugging becoming independent, I always tell people, this was about America.

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:09.000
One of the Swedish guys who was at the Co-op, I ran on the All You Cross Country Championship team for Intermurals.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:21.000
And it was me, a guy who was a very good runner and a guy from Sweden. And he told me, he said, one of my mother, and he talked about when in Europe, when they saw headlines about Alabama, wasn't about Alabama, it was about America.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:28.000
And when Russia was saying, follow us independent countries, we're the great country, we're socialism, everybody's taking care of.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:41.000
And we said, no, follow us, it's we're about freedom. And yet we weren't about freedom to a significant number. It was the VOA, we have, you know, it's a great, and that's why when I'm in Montgomery, I try to tell the whites in the blacks.

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:51.000
And many of the whites, they just re, they just overwhelmingly in the Senate and the House passed resolutions in Alabama to pardon the Scottsboro boys.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:57.000
Without one dissenting vote, not one, the governor's going to sign it.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:09.000
And, and they've now recognized and embraced this was for everybody. This movement, and many of the whites say it, it freed the whites, it freed us from our guilt.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:24.000
And it freed us from the terrorism of the clan, you know. And there were many whites who stood up, Clifford Durr + Virginia Durr + Aubrey Williams, wonderful people, you know, who really had some courage, because they lived there the whole time.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:36.000
We left, you know, because we weren't living there. Some of us stayed a little longer, whatever. I'm one of the few that's moved there. And I like Alabama now. And Alabama has changed a great deal, great deal.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:59.000
And I'll try and be shorter to respond to your questions. Well, let me mention one of their Pearson, Alabama is Millard Fuller from, from Lanett, Alabama and his wife, Linda Fuller from Montgomery, who started Habitat, who I met, I wrote the first article about Millard in housing, because that started at Koinonia Farm, Sun Chin acres, that's where it started.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:22.000
And I actually did my R&R out of America, it's over at Coenania for a couple days. So we got out of jail, they took us out there, and met Clarence L. Jordan, who was the father, you know, the founder of that place, and I became very close friends with Florence, by the way, the uncle of Hamilton, five Jordan brothers, one integrationist, that was Clarence, and who knew Hamilton Jordan quite well, and Hamilton knew his uncle Clarence quite well.

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:26.000
And I think that's what I wanted to do, and I think that was really, as you say, a R&R place for movement.

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:33.000
Well, it was its own place, too. I mean, they had their own history, but they do that in all of any two, they went up to Coenania today.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:41.000
I got to swim in a water hole, something that a boy from California, two big country things I had in the South. One was the water hole of Coenania.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:51.000
The other was that my first baseball game with the Macon Bombers in Round Oak, Georgia, which was in the middle of a cow pasture that had been, trees had been cut down, and there were cow patties on the baseball field.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:51:00.000
This was not something that a boy from LA who played on pretty good baseball fields, which used to be because my mind said, what if the ball hits the cow patty?

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:04.000
Country boys don't care about that stuff. And, of course, the ball didn't hit the cow patty.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:09.000
But that's a good segue, too. So, you know, would take us past the orientation to your assignment?

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:15.000
Yes, we had the orientation. It was an incredible orientation. And like, and the same thing with Larry Butler, the reason I say,

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:21.000
originally they got assigned one place. We got assigned to Bibb County, which was small, but we had the one of the biggest group for the 20.

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:28.000
Brandeis had a big group, which they don't seem to be interested in, or my Jewish brother in, don't seem to be interested in, small college had his biggest clubby, you say, LA Berkeley.

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:35.000
I'm working on that, and they will get interested, I guarantee you, in the next couple of years, or they will be very embarrassed, maybe this may embarrass them.

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:44.000
But Jonathan D. Sarna, who's the guy who spoke at the May-Britth Convention, who's the advisor to the National Jewish Museum, is there, I gave him the book, he hasn't called me back yet.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:56.000
I would deal with Dr. Sarna, who's very important, distinguished, and of course, Woller-Levent, all of this is not, he dropped out before he got his PhD, you say, LA, but this is my mission, and you're giving me a little form for it, so I appreciate that.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:11.000
But, so, yeah, that was the reason, and they also wanted to assign us where they could get some numbers, which was Macon, Georgia, where they had a great local leader, a great local leader, William P. Randall, William P. Randall was one.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:30.000
They had a name man named Tom Jackson, became the first black judge, who was the only black lawyer in town, there weren't many in Georgia at that time, and he went south, he returned south, and he became a good friend, he was also a former semi-pro baseball player, and of course, his family, and his wife's family, thought they were completely crazy to go south.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:41.000
He knew Mr. (William P.) Randall, and he went back, and he courageous guy, and there was also a guy named Lewis Wynn, many others, there was NAACP Youth Council, but Mr. (William P.) Randall was the town leader, he was a great guy.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:59.000
Joel Siegel talked about him on Good Morning America, he was somewhat of a mentor to Joel, although Joel never went back either, a lot of people, once they left they didn't want to go back for whatever reasons I did, because I became friends with Hosea Williams and Andy, and Mr. (William P.) Randall, and Joel went back and did a great, great piece for Good Morning America.

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:25.000
That was kind of the field producer up, but so my position was, the SCLC, we're on assignment from them, that's where they want to go, that's where we went, wasn't a great discussion, but there was some Romanicism, and also maybe we're needed more in the rural areas, but that soon ended when Hosea Williams said you are ordered to go to America, I am the general, you are the troops, you go where I tell you, that's the way it works there, and that's what we did.

00:53:25.000 --> 00:53:36.000
There was no discussion that they had and snake that whites were taking control, Hosea Williams made it very clear, who was in charge, Willie Bolden, who was an ex-Marine and a very tough guy.

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:54.000
There was no cognitive dissonance about who was going to be running anything, SCLC ran it, Hosea Williams ran it and his troops ran it, and we learned, and if we did well, we got asked to join the staff, and then we had a little more stature on the staff, but there was no confusion in our group.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:54:08.000
Hosea Williams ran it, we didn't have that problem, and William P. Randall ran it, and there was some, anyway, so that was one thing, Larry Scott Butler's group was a great story, was that, I got to tell this story, and Larry Scott is down in Florida.

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:23.000
They got assigned to some county, and then SCLC said no, Hosea Williams said we need you, or the guy that was Hosea Williams's guy there, I think is a minister here, I think is named River and Harrow, so no, we need you to go to Clayton, Alabama, Barbour County, Alabama, Alabama.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:37.000
But we already talked to these people here, we need, they were expecting us, they said, Barbour County, Alabama is the home of George C. Wallace, we need you to go raise Helen, George C. Wallace, and they said they immediately said, when do we leave?

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:51.000
And they had big demonstrations, they tore that town up, and apparently George C. Wallace came down one time, and his comment was, he said at the auto repair place, watch them march to the courthouse, and he said, that's the best look, and best dress, best dress groups, a civil rights worker I've ever seen.

00:54:51.000 --> 00:55:16.000
Because we were told, and one of the reasons that snick didn't like us, because we were told not to have beards, told to look more preppy, and to be careful about holding interracial couples in public, because it's not a criticism of the snick, they were courageous, wonderful people, but they made the white people even angrier because they flaunted it sometimes, not that it didn't need to be flaunted in some sense, but it also could get people hurt and killed, and so on.

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:27.000
And that wasn't a value, that was one of our roles, if we got killed, that brought the media and that changed things, that's a sad thing to say, but black people's lives weren't too important in those days.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:37.000
So we were told to dress well, well George C. Wallace noticed, that's the best dress group of civil rights workers I ever saw.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:49.000
Apparently, I mean that's what Larry Scott Bother told me, that was his only car, which I think is hilarious, but they registered a lot of people, that was one of the second most active movements in scope.

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:58.000
Americus was probably the first, and there are all the incidents reports in that book, there's about 20 pages of incidents reports, not everything made the incidents reports.

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:01.000
Be happy to.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:24.000
The scope of freedom, the leadership of Hosea Williams William of the Dr. King, Summer 65 student volunteers, there's Hosea Williams and Andy and St. Augustine, where Jackie Robinson by the way was, as long Jackie Robinson was in Birmingham, Jackie Robinson was in all Benny, as they call it, did Charles Sherrod, because then he talked about Jackie Robinson.

00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:32.000
Jackie, Jackie went there at Dr. King's request after the churches were burned, and they couldn't, and they couldn't get the media.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:53.000
I have an interview with Andrew Young in the book you have about that, but I have this great photo of Jackie Robinson with a white T Walker in Albany near a burned out church, and Andy said in the interview, said if you want to talk about being in harm's way, being in rural Southwest Georgia, after the churches have been burned out.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:57:02.000
The churches have been burned out by the clan, that's as much harm's way as you can be in those days, because you're not in a demonstration, they had the media there, but there's Jackie.

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:09.000
Didn't have to be there, he's from Cairo, Georgia, not too far from there, but he was on the front lines over and over again.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:16.000
One of the reasons he's doing more of my hero now, and I think that I know more about him than when I was young, but he was a healer, and God bless him.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:26.000
I'm glad he's getting the recognition. God bless Bud Selig. I got his meat bud through Andy, that's one reason Bud would want to meet me really, not that he's just because he has too many other things to do.

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:36.000
He's a nice man, he's done a great job retiring Jackie's number, Harrison Ford did a great job with this movie, and young people of all races need to know, here's a celebrity.

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:44.000
He wasn't worried about the bling, he wasn't worried about tweeting, he didn't have his own reality show, although he did play himself in a wonderful movie, Jackie Robinson's story.

00:57:44.000 --> 00:58:00.000
Typical of that era of Hollywood, well meaning, but a little hokey at places. But still a good movie, and you get to see Jackie himself, and Ruby Dee, who's Rachel Robinson, is wonderfully attractive woman as a Ruby Dee playing Jackie Robinson's wife.

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:05.000
But such a special guy, such a lesson for, and these young ball players are now learning it.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:20.000
I've just read the MLB blog, and Bryce Harper + Bryce Harper + Matt Kemp saw the movie at the White House, Prokobama showed 42, Bryce Harper + Bryce Harper + Matt Kemp was in Thuse, Bryce Harper + Matt Kemp, and you know, it's baseball has a special role in all this.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:33.000
Because of Jackie and Branch Ricky, and as Jackie said in his book, I never had it made, this was Branch Ricky's deal. I was just an actor in Branch Ricky's deal. I mean Branch Ricky conceived it all.

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:36.000
So can you tell us about the role that baseball played for you that summer?

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:44.000
Oh sure, I'm talking about baseball I love. It's actually an interesting story, which hopefully will be on a big screen or a small screen at some point.

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:49.000
But it's ironic, that was going to be my first summer not playing baseball since I was 10 years old.

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:59.000
I had been discouraged, my high school team went to the city finals, and I had played it on that, I played American Legion as a 15 year old in South Bay, where I had been the all area shortstop.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:13.000
I played, you had to get asked to be on that team after high school, and my teammates and their family are two dads, both who played professional baseball, the kids, Jeff Pentland + Jeff Pentland + Tom Griffin, and Ron McMacKinn is a buddy of Mark McGwire, Galsville Mark McGwire, and Tiger Woods.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:16.000
Very successful bunch of guys, and great athletes.

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:22.000
You know, they're dads, and they call my parents, it means you won't willing to play on the American Legion team.

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:27.000
It was a very fast group, they'd come in third in the state and little league, they're very good.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:36.000
But that summer I didn't play with them, they asked me to play, and I was getting ready for school, and I was kind of burned out because I got hurt both years, and to get much playing time.

00:59:36.000 --> 00:59:43.000
Now I really regret it, they went to the state finals in Yalfill in American Legion, and went on to great things in baseball.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:48.000
I had been on five pros on the high school team, and two more that turned down contracts, which is very rare.

00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:53.000
That's like a division one, 11 division one athletes on my high school baseball team, two in the big leagues.

00:59:53.000 --> 01:00:02.000
So I played with good guys, I had been around good baseball players, not realizing at the time how good they were, because I was more discouraged, because I wasn't playing.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:09.000
In fact, my high school coach told me, I said, I'm going to UCLA, do you think I can play there? He said, oh yeah, you couldn't play at USC, but you can play at UCLA.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:14.000
I'm not thinking, what the hell are you talking about? I'm not playing here, but as a matter of fact, our high school team was better than UCLA.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:28.000
By the time my friends were in college, they were in the Hall of Fame, Santa Barbara, Arizona State, they beat UCLA every time they played the pitchers, the pitchers were our strong suit, our fourth pitcher pitch double-lay baseball.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:33.000
So I played good baseball, I wasn't going to play that summer.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:41.000
When I came back, I got asked to actually go out at UCLA by a guy named Ray Earrington who's in the Hall of Fame, because they heard about that I played in the South, because it was in my letter.

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:50.000
But there was a guy named Willie Bowens, who still works at the VA. He came back with us. He was the one that was not invited to the opening of the Martin Luther King Memorial along with everybody else.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:54.000
I tried to tell, they had the name for a title and I developed the list.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:01:02.000
And he was an African-American, it worked three miles away. He didn't get invited. I wouldn't go. They finally invited me, but I said, if you don't invite everybody, I'm not going.

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:09.000
I didn't care that much about having my little day of glory among the UCLA group that had been opposed to having a Black for Dr. King for six years.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:20.000
I only did it because they were forced to by the NAACP and the President of the University, Mark Yudof, who hasn't forced them to put the picture back up yet.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:34.000
Willie Bowens was one of our young recruits. Some had worked with the NAACP Youth Council. Others came into the movement that summer because William P. Randall took us around to a different church every night the first week.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:47.000
We had a mass meeting, you know, what mass meetings are. And he introduced us. These white people have come down here. These white students here from UCLA, Dr. King did this, was they William P. Randall was a special, special wonderful man.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:02:00.000
Later became, there's a building name for him, his Joel Siegel said, good morning, America. He later became a Bibb County Commissioner. His son was the first state representative, his granddaughter is now the state representative and his son is a judge.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:06.000
So things do change and have changed, but Bill was the leader in the town, wonderful, just an e-man.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:17.000
And so we started recruiting young people from all the different parts of town. In Willie Bowens came out of East Macon, which is where I ended up living with the Simmons family.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:30.000
Terrell Simmons was on the Bibb Bombers as well, but I didn't know that at the time. He was gone. There was no father in home. That was a little bit of the scandal I later found because this Simmons took in two white boys and each had two daughters still at home.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:44.000
One was at Tuskegee University already, now in Mali and things are not going well in Mali. So Lucille, I'm in touch with her by email, a case of not recently. I should find out what's going on with her, but she's literally lets me know if there's a problem.

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:59.000
But anyway, so Terrell was on the team, but Willie Bowens and I became good buddies. Also William C. Randall, who was William P. Randall's nephew, later had a terrible car accident, but William C. and Willie and I, and of course I used to have one thing I really liked,

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:07.000
there were lots of willies. There was one time I was in a front yard and it was me and Willie Bowens, and the guy we were trying to get to register with, his name was Willie and the cousin's name was Willie.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:17.000
And I wrote the thing, I said lots of willies. I said, one thing that's Willie's feel is that all people are created, well, equal except Willie's, work created more equal, because I was thinking of Willie Willie Mays because he was such a great athlete.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:25.000
But anyway, so Willie and I got to be buddies, Willie's on the make, Willie Bowens was on the make and bombers, and he said, hey, maybe I can get you a try out.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:37.000
I used to wear my football jerseys in the picture here from the scope book. I was stupid enough to actually wear it in the marches, and there I, which I think now, there was a great target for the clan.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:45.000
I was like, one of the only white guys, and I'm wearing a bullseye, but I was also doing it to relate to the guys through athletics, which was my strong suit.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:51.000
So I used to call me number 10 a little bit later on in the make, because I wore my football jerseys, and I was proud I had been on the football team.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:57.000
So, the bombers were in make, sometimes they're called the Bibb Bombers as well.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:09.000
There's an article in, I think that book I showed you, with Terrell's picture in me. Terrell and I did this program, but the Georgia Sports Hall of Fame on the make and bombers, because they had into traveling exhibit on baseball and black and white about the Negro Leagues.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:19.000
And they also had, of course, they had the Negro Leagues, and they had a lot of local Negro Leagues, because they couldn't have black white Leagues, as well as they had their own Leagues.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:32.000
So, Willie got me a trial, and so we went out. Terrell had the team bus, which Terrell always worked two or three jobs. Terrell sadly had a heart attack about five years ago now, passed away, but I would always stay with Terrell.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:38.000
To people I would always see in Atlanta first were Terrell and Hosea Williams, and I would usually stand Terrell's couch.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:44.000
When I wrote the report to the President of the Congress, I stayed on Terrell's couch for two or three months, worked for Coretta Scott King.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:48.000
And I gave some money, I gave $400 back to the holiday commission, which didn't have public funding.

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:53.000
Partly because Terrell gave me free rent, so I had a little extra in. They didn't have much money.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:05:02.000
Lloyd Davis, who was my supervisor there, was a federal bureaucrat. Wonderful man, worked for Sargent Shriver, worked through Republican side when they passed the King Holiday in Reagan, signed it.

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:09.000
And his eyes got very big, you're giving me money back. It's like nobody gives money back, this is the federal government, but we didn't have federal money yet.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:14.000
We did later get it, and had it been federal money, I wouldn't have given it back, but we didn't have much money, and it was private money.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:21.000
And I just never wanted people to think that I was doing it for the money, I may have overdone that, because I ended up quite impoverished many times.

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:29.000
That's one of the reasons I was on Terrell's couch. But anyway, so Terrell had a bread truck. He had a full-time job and a bread route.

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:37.000
So his bread truck was a team bus on the weekends. So they came by 795 Center Street in East Macon, where the Simmons family lived.

01:05:37.000 --> 01:05:46.000
MMA Simmons was a professional cook, so I got real good food that summer. We got in the truck, and I think they may have told me we're playing around Oak.

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:53.000
I didn't know where Round Oak was. Go off about 40 miles away and go through this little town, which is still there.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:06:00.000
There's like a post office with some boxes in the general store. That's Round Oak, Georgia. That's it, and then you've got Country.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:08.000
So we get to this place. It's a cow pasture where the trees cut down, the diamond cut in there. That's the field.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:13.000
And then the first thing I'm noticing is the cow paddies, and I'm going, OK.

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:23.000
And so because of what I was doing, unlike Jackie Robinson, as I've said in a couple of times in articles, everybody was very nice to me.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:31.000
They didn't know if I could play or not, but they were going to give me a chance. One guy that wasn't too happy was the guy that was shortstop before I got there, because he got bumped through no fall of his own.

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:38.000
But I had just come out of this experience moving to this place where I got bumped, and I didn't want to give up any playing time. I look back at now.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:43.000
I don't think I played every inning, but I don't know, maybe he did get to play a little bit. I think I played every inning once I got there.

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:49.000
But he knew I was only going to be there for a while. But everybody else was real friendly. He would sit in the dugout. He would look at me, he didn't say anything.

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:56.000
But he wasn't happy. And I got it. I knew it. And I felt bad for him, but not that bad that I was going to coach a play.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:02.000
I loved playing baseball, and I loved practicing, but I loved playing in the game. I loved the competition.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:07.000
So this is my chance to play. I barely got to play. I got injured both years of high school.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:15.000
I played a lot in American Legion in my junior year, but I didn't, I kept getting hurt, and I kept running into Tom Griffin, who got drafted number four in the country,

01:07:15.000 --> 01:07:21.000
and was working pitch here of the year when he was 20 years old, struck out 200 for Houston, who was also a good enough hitter that he pinned shit.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:26.000
He was six foot four. I wasn't going to beat Tom Griffin out. That just wasn't going to happen.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:31.000
