01:29:11.000 --> 01:29:18.000
I think you should let him drop the charges. I'm still not sure what the charges were. At that point, I don't think I knew actually what the official charge was.

01:29:18.000 --> 01:29:29.000
I don't think to this day I don't know. I should probably go back to see if those records are available. It may have been disturbing the peace. I don't really know. Well, I heard that it was quite eloquent. That's the only thing I was told.

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:38.000
So I said, okay. So then Bill barked at the police chief a few more times, which made a big impression on me, by the way, that he was telling the police chiefs off and the police chief wanted to apologize.

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:45.000
And I, of course, spread that around. And I think the police chief spread it around with his officers. I don't think we had any more problems. Nobody else got arrested.

01:29:45.000 --> 01:29:55.000
And I was kind of the test case. It didn't work out good for the police officers. I don't know what happened to that guy. But I'd say he may have been the guy I met at the Lutheran Phil many years later. I don't know.

01:29:55.000 --> 01:30:01.000
I think they all knew about it, though. I think they all knew about it. I'm sure they all knew about it because police chief knew about it.

01:30:01.000 --> 01:30:06.000
I think they made sure they knew about it. And no one else got arrested. And we worked downtown from then on.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:14.000
And one of the things that happened was there was a guy named Denny Lee now, whose niece later had a official position with Habitat in America.

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:20.000
And Denny ended up in the Peace Corps for a long time and working out a country for a long time. And I've been in touch with him just briefly.

01:30:20.000 --> 01:30:30.000
I'd like to hear from him then and then I'd school in the Midwest. And some other people, they had a guy came up and did overalls with a gun or the 38 or some gun.

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:37.000
I don't know what caliber. And not to me, but in on the corner where we were trying to get voters and he took the gun out, stuck it in his face.

01:30:37.000 --> 01:30:42.000
And he said, if you're in this corner and now I'm going to come back to kill you. Well, that didn't work.

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:50.000
We stayed on the corners of the guy didn't come back and kill us. But I mean those kinds of things were going on in Macon, which was better than Americus where they didn't come up to you.

01:30:50.000 --> 01:30:58.000
They just shot at you. They didn't give you any warning. Later, the story was when I went back to Macon, there was a warning that if you're in town on 24 hours you're dead.

01:30:58.000 --> 01:31:05.000
And it sounded serious enough that it made me uncomfortable. But of course, at 18, I wasn't going to leave then. Bill said, no, you're going to leave.

01:31:05.000 --> 01:31:13.000
Here, time for you to go. And I was planning to leave anyway. But that's, I wrote that in something I sent you. But in America, so that was my arrest there.

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:23.000
Well, then the other time William C. Randall, who I told you about, William P. Randall's nephew, very involved, was almost 16.

01:31:23.000 --> 01:31:32.000
Had his learners permit. But then, or was 16, had a learner spent the no license. His dad is uncle had been too busy. And his dad, I don't know if you know his dad situation was.

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:40.000
But of course, when you're 16, you like to drive and impress the girls, which I knew because I was only 18. I had been 16 years too earlier and wanted to drive to impress the girls.

01:31:40.000 --> 01:31:50.000
So we were on our way home one day from downtown and William wanted me to let him drive. And he had the learner's permit, but it expired. He didn't have a license.

01:31:50.000 --> 01:32:00.000
So we got three blocks and the girls from pretty girls were in the car, black girls. And I knew why he wanted. I was sympathetic. It was a male bonding thing. And I let him drive.

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:09.000
Well, I was driving Ken's car that didn't have power steering. He knew how to drive. And he had driven his uncle Bill's car that had power steering that he could just swing around.

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:27.000
Well, they got to this corner and he tried to do the swing around like he did with one finger. The wheeled and swing. And we started into somebody's yard. Then because it was an inexperienced driver, he got panicky. And he tried to hit the brake, but he hit the gas instead and rammed into a park car in a black man's yard.

01:32:27.000 --> 01:32:37.000
Who wasn't too happy when he came out and he wasn't too confused about me because most people knew that the white people were there, but he wasn't happy about somebody just rammed into his car.

01:32:37.000 --> 01:32:42.000
Of course, I don't think that made a real good impression. There wasn't an impression that William C wanted to make on the two black girls.

01:32:42.000 --> 01:32:53.000
I had done something similar almost crashing my mom's car. So I sympathized with the whole thing. The black man was unhappy enough. He called the cops. And then William C had a knife in his pocket, which I didn't know.

01:32:53.000 --> 01:33:08.000
So they arrested him for the knife. And I think the driving and they arrested me. Now they probably could have given us a ticket, but they didn't, but they didn't want to mean about it. I mean, we were obviously guilty. And I was obviously guilty of letting a minor without a license drive.

01:33:08.000 --> 01:33:17.000
And so they took us in and we paid a $60.5 fine went to court. My dad sent them money. He wasn't thrilled about that. But of all the things were happening. That was the least of his worries.

01:33:17.000 --> 01:33:28.000
I think I had to work it off when I got back some way to do some painting for him. And so that was my second arrest and making... I don't know how I get in these situations. I just seem to get it.

01:33:28.000 --> 01:33:35.000
America is a little more dramatic. America has started telling the story about Jamo. So we got called down there.

01:33:35.000 --> 01:33:43.000
Actually quite interesting introduction to America. We went down at night. It was the night after Andrew Whatley had been killed.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:51.000
Four women were in jail. Dick Gregory was in town, leading marches. Hosea Williams had started night marches.

01:33:51.000 --> 01:34:01.000
Vivid memory of the first night in a church. There was two young African-American guys with rifle at each doors. We slept in the pews about 40 of us.

01:34:01.000 --> 01:34:11.000
What Hosea Williams wanted to do was bring in scope workers from all the projects around Georgia and Alabama. South Carolina was a little too far.

01:34:11.000 --> 01:34:19.000
And show us what a hot movement was like. Also we needed more troops for the marches because once the women were arrested and then the white guy was killed.

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:31.000
Piggly when the white kid, man, Andrew always killed. The state patrol came. 100 state patrolmen were there. The clan had a rally. There were a lot of shootings going on.

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:44.000
I mean, you know, at people, no one else got hit. And so Hosea Williams wanted troops. This was going to be the Selma of the summer. And that's actually what he said in the New York Times and LA Times articles are in my book.

01:34:44.000 --> 01:34:55.000
And so we were the reinforcements. And so that night there was a burned out car across the street that had been firebomb. So it was a lot different than making.

01:34:55.000 --> 01:35:00.000
And it was kind of in the battle and essentially in the battle from the back lines to the front line.

01:35:00.000 --> 01:35:03.000
And you find with this term, hot movement. Huh?

01:35:03.000 --> 01:35:24.000
I don't know what Hosea Williams called. I know what the way Hosea Williams described it. I think he was able to say I want you to see what a real movement is like. I think those were the, but, but a movement where the media was there, where there was mass demonstrations, where the opposition was making it life or death in some degree, which meant then that the movement was going to be a real movement.

01:35:24.000 --> 01:35:34.000
And that then that the media would portray it. The whole thing of nonviolence is to dramatize in a creative way. That's what Dr. King said in the letter from (the) Birmingham jail.

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:51.000
And create, do a creative tension nonviolently that will dramatize the injustice that will expose the racism and the injustice, which is what the whole movement was about from the Montgomery Best Boycott on, where you had the media come because of violence.

01:35:51.000 --> 01:36:02.000
And compared the entire number of people that were killed in the movement from the beginning of the Montgomery Best Boycott till 1968, the end of your period, which I think is a good period.

01:36:02.000 --> 01:36:18.000
It's less than one day in Syria or in Egypt, where they've had the Arab Spring and Barack Obama went and said model the civil rights movement, but apparently they don't have the foundation. Unfortunately, and we did have the Judeo Christian foundation here.

01:36:18.000 --> 01:36:47.000
I'm not a scholar enough about Islam. I know there are many peaceful things in Islam, but that part of Barack Obama speech, which by the way, some of the Jewish community, because I know people in the Republican Jewish Commission committee, thought that Barack Obama was being anti-Israel by saying that in Cairo, Georgia when he talked to the Egyptians at the beginning of his trip, what he was telling them is used nonviolence, which they tried and have done somewhat successfully.

01:36:47.000 --> 01:37:05.000
But the governmental structure has not supported it. We at least had a governmental structure in the United States that was based enough on law, even with the flaws in the federal government that's Nick's talk about in the corrupt federal judges of which there were some, which the Kennedy administration acknowledges they made a mistake.

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:23.000
They were lied to. I've talked to Burke Marshall. Those judges came up from Georgia and Mississippi and said, we promise you, Robert F. Kennedy called him in. And he said, if you're going to do this, you've got to follow federal law. And those judges looked him in the eye and lied to him. And they were made mistakes. There was some guy in South Georgia.

01:37:23.000 --> 01:37:52.000
They shouldn't keep getting beat up over it. It was a tough situation. I wish Nick would forgive that and understand that better and not feel so hurt about it. Same with this quote from, I know I'm getting off topic, but I want to say this, that David Giro used and said that John F. Kennedy called Nick Sunsabitches when the two guys from Birmingham, three guys came up. The transcripts are in that book. What happened in that meeting was they tried to tell Kennedy these three businessmen.

01:37:52.000 --> 01:38:12.000
Get King out of there. Get King out of there. He's causing trouble. Kennedy told them many times. And it's on tape. It's a civil rights tape at the Kennedy Library. There's a whole series to identify in my book, place in Clark. Giro misrepresent it in Frank Smith Jr, who was the African American Civil War Museum, knew the quote.

01:38:12.000 --> 01:38:33.000
Nick is still angry about the quote, John F. Kennedy is a himicrant. He called us Sunsabitches. He was complimenting him. He said, your tough Sunsabitches. What happened was seven times the white men from Birmingham said, get King out. And he told him we didn't put King in there. We can't get him out. And by the way, King ate the problem men from Birmingham didn't say evidently.

01:38:33.000 --> 01:39:02.000
You're the problem. Your laws are the problem. Change your laws. Hire some black people in your stores. And then the guy from Birmingham said, we can't have black people waiting on white people. And he said, come on. He said the military. That was difficult in 1948. People had to live in barracks together and shower together. He said hiring people in stores. And you can listen to him. He was magnificent. He said, that's nothing. That's the problem. King isn't the problem. You're the problem. And of course they negotiated that problem out.

01:39:02.000 --> 01:39:22.000
And they did hire black people. And then finally, after they said seven times, get King out. He said, look, you ought to be happy. It's King and not Snick. He said, they're tough. That John R. Lewis. Their Sunsabitches, they're tough. You don't want them. You better take King. Which is exactly by the way what Malcolm X said. You better take Dr. King and not me.

01:39:22.000 --> 01:39:44.000
Dr. John Kennedy described it the same way Malcolm X described it. But David Garrow took it out of context. And it was circulated through academia. Snick knows that quote. They're hurt by it. And I want Andy to talk about it. And he said, Dr. King talked about healing the sick. I want to heal Snick's pain until them John Kennedy who loved toughness.

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:54.000
This is a tough guy who talked about Macho 50 mile hike. He said, I told Frank Smith Jr, he said, you were tougher than Dr. King. Frank and President, he said, yes, we were tougher than Dr. King.

01:39:54.000 --> 01:40:13.000
Excuse me Frank. I hope you see this. You weren't tougher than Dr. King. Nobody was tougher than Dr. King. But you were tough. And that's what John F. Kennedy said. He was complimenting you. So to get back to my next arrest. So we were down there. They needed volunteers. Every time there was a mass meeting, they asked for volunteers. I kept raising my hand pretty soon.

01:40:13.000 --> 01:40:31.000
They knew who I was. Instead of one of 60 or 80 new white people, I was the kid that kept raising his hand and kept taking assignments. Well, as it happened, Andrew Whatley had just been killed before we got there. His funeral was that Saturday at the Methodist Church.

01:40:31.000 --> 01:40:39.000
Or maybe it was the Baptist. There was two prominent churches where the mayor and the fire chiefs and the police right across the street from each other in the same block.

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:50.000
And they needed two whites to go to tell the media that were there covering it, that there was a press conference coming up. So Rev. Eric Schiller, who was from UCLA, the minister, Rev. Eric Schiller.

01:40:50.000 --> 01:40:57.000
And we went. Now if they would have known who we were, the white people, they would have been very unhappy. We were there. But there were other people. We were in suits.

01:40:57.000 --> 01:41:08.000
And my one suit, my dad bought me its ears for 25 dollars for my high school prong. And my way, my dad said he was proud of me when I called my dad and told him I was going. It was the first time in my life.

01:41:08.000 --> 01:41:20.000
He said, no, I told you more. I said, well, he wasn't happy. I wanted me to be a musician out of baseball player. But when I called him after I decided I was very mature enough to say, I'm not going to ask my parents because if I get killed, they'll feel guilty.

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:31.000
More guilty than if I tell them I've already decided and I was 18 people were going to Vietnam. And I told him, this is what I'm going to do. The line went silent. And he said, I'm proud of you. Those were the first words out of his mouth because of his feeling not humor.

01:41:31.000 --> 01:41:42.000
He said, I'm not humored for all those things. So anyway, so they needed somebody to go to the church. Eric and I went, we took that assignment. Then they needed somebody to go to the John R. Lewis the next day to try and integrate the Baptist church and went up.

01:41:42.000 --> 01:41:58.000
Okay, you, you're going with John R. Lewis, the private me with one of the generals. I always think of it as Dr. King was the joint chief of staff general, Hosea Williams was a general, John R. Lewis was a general, Abernathy was a general, Andy was a general, Dr. King was chairman of the joint chief of staff in the movement.

01:41:58.000 --> 01:42:08.000
That's kind of how Jim Colony honey said it out and his thing. So the interesting thing was John and I go up there and John, of course, this is one of many, many, many, many, many.

01:42:08.000 --> 01:42:16.000
At a few more, many exponentially, the John R. Lewis have been involved. My first time on camera is a movement person other than the citizens council. They, they had me on camera.

01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:32.000
But so we go up there. I'm essentially an extra John was the star and I'm the extra with John and he goes up there and fire chief Henderson comes out. I think it was it was the Baptist church and he has a tape recorder because he wants to record and so nobody's misquoting him to find with us.

01:42:33.000 --> 01:42:46.000
So he says we don't want you here. We don't want you here. And that's we got actually footage of that on CBS news. And John R. Lewis says, well, but I'm a Baptist and this is a Baptist church. We'd like to worship here. I'd like to worship here.

01:42:46.000 --> 01:42:59.000
Now we don't watch. He said what about him pointing to me. We don't want him either. And he's with you. We don't want. And he said, but he said, but doesn't, doesn't Jesus say that in Christ, all men are equal. We start quoting the scripture.

01:42:59.000 --> 01:43:12.000
He starts quoting Jesus Christ because John's been to some done is what's not a minister because he dropped out of seminary just before he graduated, but he had been the seminary. So he knew scripture started quoting scripture to fire chief Henderson. Fire just Henderson got very flustered.

01:43:13.000 --> 01:43:28.000
That doesn't matter here. That doesn't matter here. It's just a chapel. Rest these people. Rest these people. So that fire chief Henderson was was quite unable to answer John R. Lewis when he started quoting scripture. He couldn't figure out a good answer as to why Jesus was went on us in the church.

01:43:29.000 --> 01:43:44.000
So fire chief Henderson came and we left. We didn't get arrested, but I think I don't know if we said we'll be back, but we came back. So that was one of the big deals. And that was on national news and some of my baseball friends saw me. They've got back and they're like, well, I didn't sell you on national news.

01:43:44.000 --> 01:43:56.000
And that was on all the national, all the three networks night. It was a big story. That's where all the media was. Once Andrew Whatley had been killed. There were media there anyway. But once there was a killing, of course, the media wanted to see if they're going to be more killing whatever.

01:43:56.000 --> 01:44:09.000
They were doing a great job. Tom Brokall was there did a great job. I mean, the media did was doing great work in those days. I shouldn't have said it in that way, but obviously that brings, you know, it's not the planes that land that bring the media. It's the ones that don't land.

01:44:09.000 --> 01:44:23.000
So we were then working. I got shot at that week at close range twice. And then we went back to the church the next week. That week, John took his group to the Baptist church.

01:44:23.000 --> 01:44:33.000
And Willie Bolden took a group to the Methodist church. I don't think anybody, I don't know, somebody may have gone to the Methodist church that first week too. I don't know. I was at the Baptist church with John.

01:44:33.000 --> 01:44:42.000
And that photo actually ended up in Ebony magazine eight months later. They did a special article about the movement and Christianity. And they talked about the Americus churches.

01:44:42.000 --> 01:44:53.000
And that was part of Hosea Williams's plan. Hosea Williams said the media is here. We're going to dramatize the churches. And nobody from the white community could have said that was unfair.

01:44:53.000 --> 01:45:05.000
Or today could say it because Lena Turner, who had been a snake worker who later worked with scope. Because at that point, a number of people in snake also worked and were paid by a CLC. Lena Turner was one of them. She was also one of the women arrested.

01:45:05.000 --> 01:45:16.000
She went after the 64 Civil Rights Act of 1964 to every white church in town, every church in Americus letter in except the first Baptist and the first Methodist or the big important people work.

01:45:16.000 --> 01:45:25.000
So we knew who those two, they knew and the local people told Hosea Williams that. So that was part of the plan. We're going to expose this unchristinlike behavior.

01:45:25.000 --> 01:45:36.000
The difference at the Methodist church is their national body had passed an edict saying no one could be refused. I'm not sure that Lena knew that at the time or let them know.

01:45:36.000 --> 01:45:39.220
But the next week, I was a

01:45:39.220 --> 01:45:49.000
Turner. I believe Lena. Lena is still alive in Detroit last I heard. I tried to contact her and she did not come down for the

01:45:49.000 --> 01:46:05.000
American Sumter County Movement. They have an organization which is very active. Samohoan is the co-chair. Gloria Wise, who was one of the other women arrested, is deceased but her sister Jewel unfortunately had a stroke as a dear friend, is involved with that.

01:46:05.000 --> 01:46:21.000
Amy Peacamble was one of the other women arrested there listed in my book in the articles. She's still alive. But that's why I think it's be great if you talk to Samohoan. That's a very active organization that is not embedded and are teaching their history.

01:46:21.000 --> 01:46:32.000
I think Sumter County more than any county, more than Albany, more than Lowndes County, Alabama because of Coenania and because of being the founding place of Habitat.

01:46:32.000 --> 01:46:47.000
And also Andersonville National Historic Site is there, the Civil War Cemetery. So it's an amazing history from the Civil War up through the movement. And the legacy is also Habitat, which is part of Coenania, which is very positive.

01:46:47.000 --> 01:46:50.000
And unfortunately some of the other legacies are not so positive.

01:46:50.000 --> 01:47:02.000
But America says a glorious story. But I'm in Sumter County. So anyway, so as we're going up to the Methodist Church, Willie Bowling is leading the group because he's one of Dr. King's lieutenants, one of his A's lieutenants.

01:47:02.000 --> 01:47:18.000
Now Rev. Willie Bolden, not at the time, it wasn't Rev. Willie Bolden. And he said, Willie, he said to me, I can't get arrested today. I'm leading the movement here. You lead the group. Why he picked me? I mean, I'd only been around for 10 days of the people there.

01:47:18.000 --> 01:47:30.000
I guess I had been volunteering more. So I then led that group to the Methodist Church. And we were told, you can't come in. They met us in the line and some of them had plaque jacks.

01:47:30.000 --> 01:47:43.000
And they said, you can't worship here. And I said, can we, and I think either he told me or I knew that, I don't know how it was. But I think we knew we wanted to say a prayer if we couldn't go.

01:47:43.000 --> 01:47:59.000
So I said, can we say a prayer? And they said, yes, before we were arrested. And you say, you're the group of most of these LA students, Chuck Ham, any lanes, Fonken, all of us that were on this telegram that Richard "Rick" Tuttle had sent.

01:47:59.000 --> 01:48:11.000
And I read the picture that was on every front page in LA Times, LA, general constitution, New York Times. They shot the picture from across the street. And so I'm in the front. So I'm barely seeing you can barely see me.

01:48:11.000 --> 01:48:23.000
And I do have the news footage of it, though, which is kind of interesting to watch. And so also interesting to listen to this Stanford interview where I'm much less hyper than I think I came back with post-traumatic stress.

01:48:23.000 --> 01:48:37.000
And it had been more hyper ever since than I ever was before. And I thought I wasn't hyper before. But anyway, so I, we now said the prayer and then they arrested us, took us to jail. And then John R. Lewis had another interesting moment. We get in the jail with Sheriff Fred B. Chappell.

01:48:37.000 --> 01:48:49.000
And he said, okay, what's over here? They would, the polite term in those days was NIGRA's. And of course, the joke in the movement was, the white people said, well, that's our southern accent. We can't say need grow.

01:48:49.000 --> 01:49:00.000
Because we don't say grow. We say grrr. We say NIGRA. We're not being rude. And so what black people would say, those white people can say need. And they can say grow. So they can say NIGRA.

01:49:00.000 --> 01:49:06.000
And so, but, but Sheriff Fred B. Chappell said NIGRA. And that was probably better than he said most of the time, frankly.

01:49:06.000 --> 01:49:23.000
This is who Jimmy Carter had said was my dear friend. Because Jimmy Carter had a lot of dear friends down there because he was from planes. The man that beat Bill Rao next to David Bell, whose family I stayed with, was the former state rep who served with Jimmy Carter.

01:49:23.000 --> 01:49:35.000
Jimmy by the way stayed neutral, which is not the worst thing in the world. He ordered both the clan and the movement and the reporters, which is written about by the AJC guy in his book, the one that pulls her prize, office property.

01:49:35.000 --> 01:49:51.000
What Florence Jordan told me was that Jimmy knew that he couldn't stay in business if he took sides. I mean, if he showed any sympathy, he wasn't going to have a peanut business. And he had kids and everything else. So he did his missionary work, which he did do at the time outside of planes.

01:49:51.000 --> 01:50:01.000
But he did tell the clan came and wanted him to join. He said, get off my property. I'm not joining. He was a Navy veteran. And the New York Times came and he said, get off my property. Not talking to you.

01:50:01.000 --> 01:50:11.000
And anyway, but, but, but the guy that served with him was the one who beat Bill Rao. It would have been the death, but David fell on top of him. But anyway.

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:19.000
So what happened in the jail? So Sheriff Fred B. Chappell said, niggas over here, what people over here? And John said, well, that's a violation of the Civil Rights Act of 1964.

01:50:19.000 --> 01:50:30.000
In 64, you can't segregate us in the jail. You can't do that. And Sheriff Fred B. Chappell said, well, you may run the streets, but you don't run this jail. And John said, well, I don't run this. He said, yes, you do, but you don't run this jail. Get over there.

01:50:30.000 --> 01:50:38.000
And so they segregated us in the jail, which of course gave John a chance to talk to the two guys that have been arrested for shooting Andrew Whatley.

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:51.000
He claimed what's innocent. They eventually went to prison. I don't know what the details were as far as what actually happened. But the shooting was in retaliation for a lot of violence directed towards the marchers.

01:50:51.000 --> 01:51:01.000
And that night, those guys said enough, we're not going to have our people. They were throwing broken glass at kids. And it was not, and they were shooting at people.

01:51:01.000 --> 01:51:09.000
I don't know one of the other nice things that was happening in America was as they released people not from the county jail, but the city jail, which was downtown. I was in the county jail.

01:51:09.000 --> 01:51:20.000
Fire station was across the street. And the firemen had hunting slingshots and ball bearings. And they were shooting the slingshots, which could have killed somebody, put their eye out.

01:51:20.000 --> 01:51:27.000
They may have been good enough shots that they weren't hitting people, but they were ricocheting off as they knew when they were being released and they were shooting.

01:51:27.000 --> 01:51:41.000
The other story in there that's amazing is Warren Fortson, who was Jimmy Carter's lawyer, who came out for a biracial council, which the whites wouldn't agree to in the beginning, was actually run out of town. He was a white guy.

01:51:41.000 --> 01:51:56.000
And his brother was Ben W. Fortson Jr, the sitting secretary of state. And to me, that really showed how bad the repression was. If the brother of the sitting secretary of state in Atlanta, 150 miles away, could not be protected.

01:51:56.000 --> 01:52:07.000
I mean, this is the brother of the secretary of state, who knows the governor, who was the liberal cross-enders, and can't mobilize his tape patrol that he doesn't, he feels he has to leave for his own safety.

01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:16.000
It's pretty dangerous. And that article is in my book and he left Warren Fortson left. But they did create a biracial council within about two weeks.

01:52:16.000 --> 01:52:26.000
After those demonstrations, there was a biracial council because the white leaders were getting terrible publicity and they knew that they were going to lose.

01:52:26.000 --> 01:52:31.000
So the other guy I would like to mention is a guy named Albert "Red" Heffner. Have you ever heard of Albert "Red" Heffner?

01:52:31.000 --> 01:52:42.000
Albert "Red" Heffner was then working for the community of relation service. I also met Jack Nelson of the LA Times down there. But America was where I got to meet, kind of where I proved myself in that all you could say.

01:52:42.000 --> 01:52:59.000
And where I met a lot of really substantial, interesting people because of what was happening there. Albert "Red" Heffner was running out of the hot ink harder, the third, the one that worked for Jimmy Carter wrote a book called So the Heffners Left McComb.

01:52:59.000 --> 01:53:08.000
The interesting story was Albert "Red" Heffner's eldest daughter was Miss Mississippi in the Miss USA page. Miss America page, the main pageant.

01:53:08.000 --> 01:53:17.000
And she was what Virginia Durr called. Virginia Durr's autobiography is called Virginia Durr. If you know much about Virginia Durr, you should read her.

01:53:17.000 --> 01:53:25.000
I got to meet her once she was quite elderly. But the magic circle, you know what the magic circle was. Magic Circle for white woman was, Virginia said,

01:53:25.000 --> 01:53:37.000
Zer said, as long as white women in the South stayed inside the magic circle, they were catered to. They were taken care of. They were unapetrable. And of course they couldn't be defiled by any black men.

01:53:37.000 --> 01:53:49.000
Of course, well, one of the excuses was, you want them to marry your sister or whatever, you know. But so they were put on a pedestal. It was a great story from Selma. There was actually an interracial couple in Selma.

01:53:49.000 --> 01:54:02.000
The daughter was from a prominent family. So prominent that the whites couldn't retaliate against the black guy. It was still there by 65. You know how they handled that problem? The family just decided she was no longer white.

01:54:02.000 --> 01:54:12.000
That's all the problem. She was no longer white. So there was no longer a problem. And the town, all the white people were, was she not white.

01:54:12.000 --> 01:54:27.000
That's how you, because she was, she was too prominent to kill. And the black guy was too prominent to kill. You couldn't do it because they were two. They were one of the town leaders. So how do you solve that problem and sell my Alabama? She ceases to be white.

01:54:27.000 --> 01:54:41.000
And this is absolutely true. You can, I forget the guy's name, but that's a great story from Selma. So the South was so conflicted with all this. Another story that's so interesting is that. So anyway, so in Janet Merritt was a woman who was a state rep after the gang.

01:54:41.000 --> 01:54:54.000
She was a state rep after the guy who was beating people up. She stepped Virginia Durr. She later got defeated, but she was in for three terms. Another one of five, one of her, was a great artist. I got one of her. I got to meet all these wonderful people.

01:54:54.000 --> 01:55:19.000
But anyway, so Albert "Red" Heffner was down there. And he had to leave McComb, Mississippi because all he did is have some blacks and whites at his house to discuss the problem. He was an insurance man. They poisoned his dog, they threatened his family. And he left and he got taken in by the community relation service run by LeRoy Collins, former governor of Florida, who Andrew Young was a friend of, and he was down there.

01:55:19.000 --> 01:55:45.000
And I got to know him and a very, you know, press of guy. And he was now working for the Department of Justice. So he, and, and, you know, and of course the younger daughter who wasn't Miss Mississippi kind of got it that the family had to leave. The one that was Miss Mississippi. Why don't I have to leave my friends? I'm Miss Mississippi. I don't want to leave my, you know, I mean, she was on the pedestal. Virginia Durga Virginia Durr when she worked with Eleanor Roosevelt in the New Deal.

01:55:45.000 --> 01:56:14.000
Wonderful lady. So I and all same with Foreign Student and in the Clarence Student out of Quentin. So, so we were, we got put in there with about three of the white guys that had been throwing broken glass at black kids and one civil rights worker. And they were having a card game when they finished the card game, they were going to beat him up. Then six of us came in so that that part was over. They didn't, they weren't going to beat him up. But they, they really were one of their, I was a number of times where I had the question on balance.

01:56:14.000 --> 01:56:29.000
One was when Jetson Ford put his gun in the belt when we were going out to get the people out in the county areas of Sumter County, which I was actually happy about because I was, I'd already been shot at. So, but I was still a conflict. This is not what Dr. King would really approve of.

01:56:29.000 --> 01:56:43.000
To the matter, we're not in a demonstration. The other time was listening to these white guys and it was ugly. It was similar sort of to the Ben Chapman character that was a true character in the Jackie Robinson with the manager of the Phillies who was the worst antagonist.

01:56:43.000 --> 01:56:55.000
The worst antagonist and the worst in the language. And I literally, I think I had to put my hands over my ears and, and it was making me sick where I wanted to beat the crap out of these guys, which was against the rules.

01:56:55.000 --> 01:57:08.000
And they were literally trying to provoke people? No, no. They were just, that's just who they were. They were just talking about us and they were talking about black people. And that's just how they talked. They were not nice people. They were not of the higher classes, let's say.

01:57:08.000 --> 01:57:19.000
And so, but I, you know, I had they started a fight. I could have defended, but I couldn't go attack them. That would have been against what I had pledged myself to nonviolence.

01:57:19.000 --> 01:57:30.000
But it made me very, very angry. I mean, I did, I, I want to, and it probably connected emotionally to the, to hear in Kaikwondo. I was like, I didn't think of it at the time, but it was very deep connection.

01:57:30.000 --> 01:57:48.000
And I just wanted to shut up. You know, I, I think, but nonviolence was you, you ignored them. You turned the other cheek. And by the time I left, that was, I was pretty much said, you know, many of us could practice it. We could not be a doctor king could live it.

01:57:48.000 --> 01:57:58.000
Hosea Williams was not a nonviolent guy. It's one reason Stink doesn't like him so much because he got in their face. You know, he got very angry at people. He, he had a temper. He didn't put up with stuff.

01:57:58.000 --> 01:58:26.000
But he practiced nonviolence during the movement and in demonstrations. He walked across the bridge into the end of the battle. I found out by the summer, I could not practice. I could not be spiritually a nonviolent person. Maybe too much football. Maybe Kaikwondo was young, maybe too angry. In my core, I, I had enough abuse. I hadn't, I didn't want to take it anymore. And I also had post-traumatic stress at that point from the shootings and the stress of being scared every day.

01:58:26.000 --> 01:58:41.000
I mean, if you're scared, you know, if you have the fight or flight syndrome and you can't do either, you internalize and that's not very good for you. And plus getting, I got shot at from six feet away. I got, you know, from the next car, which told us, told us, told us, scared me.

01:58:41.000 --> 01:58:48.000
Is that while you were trying to write a servo? No, that was when I was trying to organize a major in this, which was going to be a great opening scene in my movie after the movie helped.

01:58:48.000 --> 01:59:01.000
But ironically, amazingly, really, I'm an Americus. Who'd I run into? A guy from Grant High School name Rich Adler, who was, I was a sports center. He was in the Hall of Fame as a gymnast. He was a ring guy.

01:59:01.000 --> 01:59:09.000
Like most gymnasts, small and very muscular because they have to low weight, you know, in their bottom. So a lot of little guys with big arms.

01:59:09.000 --> 01:59:24.000
Rich was about five seven, dark hair Jewish, and he had joined SNCC somewhere in other. I don't know if you want to, I don't know where we want it. What's a college? But somehow he's gotten involved with SNCC. He's down there. And in between the week going to churches, I run into Rich. Hey Rich, how you doing?

01:59:24.000 --> 01:59:31.000
You haven't seen him in a year because I've been a college. Maybe I'm trying to think if he was a, I think he was a year ahead of me. Maybe not him. He was either in my classroom or your head of me.

01:59:31.000 --> 01:59:46.000
But I knew him and he was a good athlete and a lot of the athletes knew each other. We didn't run in the same group. But I know he was in the Hall of Fame because I wrote about him. And I don't know if it was my junior year or my senior year. But he was a real good gymnast. He was all the, all the gymnasts.

01:59:46.000 --> 01:59:52.000
And he had been beaten. He's in the news accounts in my book. He had been surrounded by group of whites and beaten up and broken through.

01:59:52.000 --> 02:00:04.000
He was a strong guy. And he was also in theory, pledged non-violence. But he wasn't going to beat, you know, 10 guys were going to beat him up. So he broke through the crowd and got away. But they did beating.

02:00:04.000 --> 02:00:15.000
And it was in the paper he got injured, whatever. But he came to me and he said, hey, I'm organizing in May Junin. These may is working 80 hours for $20 a week. Let's organize a May Junin.

02:00:15.000 --> 02:00:27.000
Well, that didn't come from Hosea Williams. You know, Hosea Williams was doing the churches and the marches. But I thought, yeah, that sounds like a good idea. The little did I know.

02:00:27.000 --> 02:00:40.000
Well, the other unfortunate thing was Fred Hoffman, the guy who made the movie Be Somebody, who was an Air Force veteran who was 29. His car was there. He had a Citroen.

02:00:40.000 --> 02:00:48.000
I'd probably like a 1963 Citroen. Let me tell you, I don't think there were any other Citroens in the state of Georgia. There certainly was no other Citroens.

02:00:48.000 --> 02:00:58.000
I think you may have had Georgia plates on by that time, but it didn't matter. There were no Citroens in America. And all the white people knew that if there was a Citroen, it must be an outsider.

02:00:58.000 --> 02:01:09.000
And that was the car I had. I had Fred's car. Not good thinking on my 18 year. I think I was probably wearing my number 10 jersey and driving a Citroen, going to try and organize a May Junin.

02:01:09.000 --> 02:01:21.000
That was a third strike. That was not good. But risk condensed. So I just, you know, I didn't think about it very clearly. There was so much going on that, hey, we're on the origin. Okay, good. All right. What are we? What are you doing?

02:01:21.000 --> 02:01:28.000
He said, well, we got to go around and pick up the mage and take him to a meeting at the Freedom Center. Freedom Center is... There's the Freedom Center.

02:01:28.000 --> 02:01:36.000
That was a little building owned by Barnum's family, the owned Barnum's Funer Home, which was one of the other centers of the movement there whose family had gone to jail.

02:01:36.000 --> 02:01:48.000
The wealthy family. You know, the barbers could head into pennant clients. They could... They were independent. The funeral people and the ministers. Everybody else was beholden to the white community, including the teachers and those segregated days.

02:01:48.000 --> 02:01:57.000
So we went around to a couple of places. They said no. The women went... They were... They seemed fearful. One of the few times I really saw people fearful.

02:01:57.000 --> 02:02:05.000
And this was again, this was the week that Andrew Whatley had been killed. State Patrol had been sent there. The planet had a rally.

02:02:05.000 --> 02:02:12.000
Lustromatics was in town. It was a pretty busy week in Americus Georgia. And then I've got some of the news footage from that.

02:02:12.000 --> 02:02:21.000
But the mage wouldn't get in the car with two white boys. I think the other thing was that we're not getting in the car with you two white boys because they ain't going to go over big with the white community.

02:02:21.000 --> 02:02:28.000
And they may hate you more than us, but they may miss you and hit us when they shoot at you. So they wouldn't come in the car.

02:02:28.000 --> 02:02:38.000
So I remember very vividly. And in those days, in most of the black communities, there was not a ghetto. It wasn't even so much the other side of the tracks.

02:02:38.000 --> 02:02:45.000
In the least the communities where I was, the black neighborhoods were scattered throughout the downtown here.

02:02:45.000 --> 02:02:53.000
The fancy white neighborhood could be a little black poor neighborhood here, little black poor neighborhood. You know, there were pockets, two or three maybe.

02:02:53.000 --> 02:02:58.000
So we had to drive through the white from a black neighborhood through white downtown or to another black neighborhood.

02:02:58.000 --> 02:03:04.000
And as we came out from the last group that we were talking, we couldn't get anybody to come. We gave up at that point.

02:03:04.000 --> 02:03:13.000
I noticed there was a pick. I think I may have noticed the pickup truck on the way in, but I definitely noticed it on the way out.

02:03:13.000 --> 02:03:24.000
And as we left it followed. And I noticed because things were going on. I mean, you know, I, that was the first time I got shot at. But, you know, it was a dangerous time.

02:03:24.000 --> 02:03:38.000
So I, I noticed there had been bricks. The guy I was living with at David Bell's family, Bill Raul had 13 stitches in his chin. They had driven by and throwing a brick at him, hitting with a brick, then chasing him and beating him with sticks.

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:49.000
And he had also broken some fingers and then David through David was 17 later in the military. He's in Albany, he's a social worker now David Bell. You might try and find David.

02:03:49.000 --> 02:03:58.000
And I'd stayed in touch with his mom for years. And I think David may be divorced now with three kids. But he was stationed at Fort Benning for many years. He was a, you know, in the military for 20 years.

02:03:58.000 --> 02:04:11.000
Ironically, Bill Raul's brother was a, a chaplain in the military for Benning when Bill went missing my only contact with the FBI that summer. I have a file now from the thread and making at the gas station.

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:21.000
Was I called the Albany, the Albany office. Bill, we were always told to keep tabs. If somebody, if you're going out, tell people when you're coming back. And if you're not back, then try and find out what happened.

02:04:21.000 --> 02:04:43.000
So Bill was gone. You know, he had beaten beaten up. And I didn't, he was missing essentially six hours late. So I called the FBI field office in Albany. And I, and I got one of the ones that Dr. King criticized for being a southern who wasn't similar to that, that it was a movement. And it was, oh yeah. He said, you call us back if you find the body.

02:04:43.000 --> 02:04:56.000
Click. That was how much they were interested in helping. That was not the case of the FBI agents sent after John Doar got the complaint that I made to Joel Siegel that Joel Siegel sent to him. That's in that book.

02:04:56.000 --> 02:05:06.000
You can read their interviews of the people they chased are all over Georgia who had made the threats and you're comming their communication with power service stations, which convinced power service station.

02:05:06.000 --> 02:05:17.000
It's not a good enough excuse to say that you're hiring people that aren't taking down the white only signs. You better take down the white only signs at your gas stations or you're going to be in trouble.

02:05:17.000 --> 02:05:32.000
It's not going to be anybody else, but your corporate office and the white only signs came down. But anyway, so we the car followed us. And because I knew of the brick being thrown as the car came up the side of us.

02:05:32.000 --> 02:05:45.000
I can't remember. I'm trying to write it for the screenplay now. And I don't really remember if I said anything like look out, rich or whatever. But I started rolling down the window, not that Fred had air conditioning. The windows are probably half done anyway.

02:05:45.000 --> 02:05:57.000
Because I didn't want to brick hit the window and shatter. Not that it may have been shattered for a flash. But because I was bunking and sharing a bedroom with Bill and he had been hit by a brick, I was thinking more brick than gun.

02:05:57.000 --> 02:06:10.000
Instead what happened the car came up was a pickup truck. Gun came out about this far away. I mean, I'm here. I'm the driver. The passenger car pulls up. The passenger sticks the gun out, bang, bang, bang.

02:06:10.000 --> 02:06:22.000
As soon as I saw the gun, I ducked, rich ducked, heard the shots, hit the break and started looking for the bullet holes.

02:06:22.000 --> 02:06:37.000
And they took off the guy, the shooters left. And there were no bullet holes, which was very confusing to me because I wasn't far away. To this day, I don't know whether the bullets went through the window or where they were blanks.

02:06:37.000 --> 02:06:45.000
Now I've talked to somebody in the military. For whatever reason they said, I don't think it was bullet. I don't think they would have gotten all that trouble with blanks.

02:06:45.000 --> 02:06:58.000
On the other hand, it was a good way to scare me and not kill me because it scared me. It scared both of us. Rich I think did leave. I've only talked to him once since then. I've tried to find him. Actually, I haven't been able to find him.

02:06:58.000 --> 02:07:08.000
And he said, I thought I was driving. I said no, Rich. I was driving. But he had already been, and they may have been going after him. He may have been, but I had already been to the church.

02:07:08.000 --> 02:07:23.000
So he had been already beaten up. I had been to the church. We were both ID'd at that point. See, when we first came down, one of the reasons I got sent to the church for the funeral was they didn't know who we were. But it didn't take long. By that time, both Rich and I were known.

02:07:23.000 --> 02:07:34.000
So I don't know who they were following or they were certainly following the car. And to this day, I don't know. The next day I got shot at it again. I heard the bullet hit the bushes, so I know that was a real bullet.

02:07:34.000 --> 02:07:45.000
And that was I was just walking with about four black guys. The truck came by. I don't know the same truck or not. I didn't look close enough at the truck the first day. That was all pretty quick first day.

02:07:45.000 --> 02:07:59.000
But the second day, I was scared. It was terrifying. I dove in the bushes. The black guys knew instinctively they would be shooting at me. The whites, I didn't know if you've heard this before. The whites hated the white civil rights workers more than they hated the black.

02:07:59.000 --> 02:08:09.000
They understood the blacks. They wanted their freedom. Why the hell were the white people helping them? We were race straighters. We were white niggers. We were called white niggers sometimes.

02:08:09.000 --> 02:08:21.000
So the black guys knew that if they were shooting at somebody and a lot of black people will tell you this freedom whiteers Bob and Bob, who's used to the freedom whiteers, is white Helen Singleton.

02:08:21.000 --> 02:08:36.000
And Bob and Helen Singleton. Helen is on what's his name book, Freedom Writer Book on the cover. I was at Ritt Tuddo's house at a dinner with Helen with Helen with somebody with a journalist. She told him, no, when we were freedom writers, they hated the white some more.

02:08:36.000 --> 02:08:47.000
Among moving people that are honest with you, they'll tell you that. And it makes sense. They understood the black people. They didn't like them. They hated them. But they knew why they were doing it. Why were we doing it? We were traders.

02:08:47.000 --> 02:09:15.000
And they wanted to make us an example. Without us, the black people, they could kill them without its rebel. So they weren't thinking very clearly because once they killed us, that was even worse. But the black guys laughed at me when I dove in the bushes that second day. They didn't dive in the bushes. I was afraid they were going to come back. I was scared. I was very scared by this. Now I told people, and I think it's really true. The first day really scared me. But it went away. I mean, I was shook up and I told people it's in the incident reports.

02:09:15.000 --> 02:09:31.000
And I think the group from Macon didn't want me to stay because they were afraid I was going to get killed. But the second one had a far more lasting effect. If it happens once, they will happen once. Never going to happen again. When it happens, the second time, you don't know when the third time is. And particularly, even to the state, I don't like cars that follow me.

02:09:31.000 --> 02:09:42.000
When I drove between making an America, the rest of that summer, no one ever passed me. I knew I had promote supposed dramatic stress. When I got back, I stayed two weeks extra, almost three weeks extra for the election and Macon.

02:09:42.000 --> 02:09:54.000
That was my thing for the people in Macon. No, you can't leave. We need you here. Everybody knows number 10. I said, no, it was they want to put me on the staff. They want me to be in America. I'll come back. You see, you're deserting the people in Macon. No, I'll come back. I'll work in the election.

02:09:54.000 --> 02:10:11.000
We were our physical project was 10 weeks, June 14th, August 28th. The election was September 15th in Macon. I said, well, gosh, school doesn't start till the 19th. We registered all these voters. We registered over 3000 voters in Macon. Now that our job is to get them to vote, that's the whole point.

02:10:11.000 --> 02:10:18.000
Everybody else decided they wanted to leave. They did their time. They did their tour. They were everybody left.

02:10:18.000 --> 02:10:34.000
Moral was going to come back, but he left too. Eventually, he did come back. Moral Ruse. I stayed. Anyway, when I got back, and that was when I got the threat from the client the night before that, when I got back, when I was driving down to see Ken Long, I was on the Long Beach Freeway.

02:10:34.000 --> 02:10:46.000
The other people also, they drove back. They had time to decompress. From a night 24 hours earlier, they said, if you're still in town, 24 hours are dead. 24 hours later, I landed in LA. I had no decompression time.

02:10:46.000 --> 02:10:48.000
Did this threat come from?

02:10:48.000 --> 02:10:53.000
The night of the election, oh, you didn't read that in my article. I said, that was in the neighborhood article.

02:10:53.000 --> 02:11:07.000
When I stayed for the election in Macon, it was the first black who had run since reconstruction. It was for water commissioners. They said in the article they changed it for commissioners. It was a commissioner, but it was Reverend Marcus Moon. He was a barber and minister.

02:11:07.000 --> 02:11:16.000
If you didn't have a full-time church, you needed to support himself. But he stood up. He said, OK, go Randall needed a candidate. He decided to be the candidate.

02:11:16.000 --> 02:11:29.000
In the morning of the election, they changed every voting polling place in Macon. At least we knew we had an impact. They put the directions in Boxcore Print. Now many of the black people had not had good educations.

02:11:29.000 --> 02:11:35.000
The tiny print was very hard to read. Plus, I think some of them may have been in white neighborhoods. I don't know.

02:11:35.000 --> 02:11:50.000
But all of our plans for getting people to the polls were thrown. And of course, the white people that did this knew they were doing that. That's why the Voting Rights Act of 1965 needs to be kept active and approved so that will never happen again.

02:11:50.000 --> 02:12:08.000
And I am sympathetic to Alabama and other places that said we haven't had this discrimination in years. The problem is, this is politics. This has nothing to do with race. This could happen. This probably happens in places that I don't know the Voting Rights Act of 1965. If they can get away with it, excuse it, the language for lawyers.

02:12:08.000 --> 02:12:21.000
If lawyers run things, they figure a way to get around and manipulate laws. That's what the adversary system, which I don't like, that they've been involved with civil rights law, sets up. If we can get away with it, we do it.

02:12:21.000 --> 02:12:34.000
It doesn't matter whether you're interested or guilty, you do what you can get away with. That's part of the adversary system. I understand there's a value to that as well. But that's why the Voting Rights Act of 1965. That's why Scope and Richard "Rick" Tuttle is the one that said this in my book.

02:12:34.000 --> 02:12:48.000
Here's what Richard "Rick" Tuttle said, how important Scope was, which is ironic because he's quoted in my book and I give him credit for it. The Voting Rights, some that happened in March, Voting Rights Act of 1965 was stalled till the 6th of August, watched blew up on the 11th.

02:12:48.000 --> 02:13:08.000
If the Voting Rights Act of 1965 and all the moral support of the Churches, the White Community Labor Unions was powerful supporting the Voting Rights Act of 1965. If we hadn't got it done by the 6th and the Watts riots or Watts riots had happened, some of that white support through the Churches and the unions would have been weakened.

02:13:08.000 --> 02:13:23.000
There was always going to be a Voting Rights Act of 1965. The key question was exactly what's still being debated, the enforcement clause. That's what the Southerners were stalling for and negotiating for no enforcement clause.

02:13:23.000 --> 02:13:52.000
Because, of course, without an enforcement clause, the law would have been meaningless, just like the one in 57. That's why Scope was very, very critical to the Voting Rights Act of 1965, both pushing it out of committee. And as history, as Richard "Rick" Tuttle, who's a PhD in history, explained to me, apparently not to you, why Scope was important was because we kept the pressure on and got that vote signed before the first explosion in the North, the worst of the first explosion.

02:13:52.000 --> 02:14:15.000
So, but when I was driving on the Long Beach Freeway, whether it's talking about post-traumatic stress, the same lights that bothered me and the South still bothered me and I didn't want them to follow me and I thought, wait a second, that's not right. That's like the guy said, it's not right when the white woman called him or his mother. I said, that's not right. I'm not in Georgia anymore. Those people aren't following me.

02:14:15.000 --> 02:14:25.000
But emotionally, I don't want, I don't like, I wanted to get away from them. I didn't want them to pass me. Once that car passed me, I never let another car pass me the rest of the summer and I still don't like cars to pass me.

02:14:25.000 --> 02:14:44.000
Because I, I mean, you and I know intellectually and I pretty much know emotionally, that next car ain't going to shoot at me again, but I'm not 100% sure. That's what post-traumatic stress is. Just like these guys who come back from the IUDs, I don't know what they go through because they've had far more, although we have a gun stuck in your face and bullet shot, that's pretty scary.

02:14:44.000 --> 02:14:58.000
But I have to watch myself now that when cars are behind me, I have to call myself down and say, what's going on? This is your kicking end, just relax. It's not 1965.

02:14:58.000 --> 02:15:12.000
But when I first got back, that was just one of many things I got depressed after that and no one really knew what it was back then. They called it Battle Fatigue and actually I did see the campus psychologist at UCLA.

02:15:12.000 --> 02:15:23.000
And they said, well, people from the Peace Corps, they didn't associate it with a danger. What they said, because I don't know if I, I don't know if I verbalized the government or if I understood that part.

02:15:23.000 --> 02:15:36.000
But they said people coming back from the Peace Corps from such an intense emotional experience being bonded so closely every day with people in very intense work sometimes had readjustment things.

02:15:36.000 --> 02:15:45.000
And that's what they told me at UCLA when I made one attempt to figure out what was going on. It's all a cherry confinement.

02:15:45.000 --> 02:15:54.000
That's the second movie. The movie in the South is called The Summer in the South and if that ever gets made, the one in LA would be called a Fall in LA.

02:15:54.000 --> 02:16:00.000
112 days. And I tell you, 112 days is not a long, long time in jail, but it's a pretty long time in jail.

02:16:00.000 --> 02:16:07.000
How do I ask about that quickly, but I just want to follow up on, because I think the PTSD in movement, Burad, this is a very important thing.

02:16:07.000 --> 02:16:18.000
Very important for SNCC. I don't think they understand it. I don't think the SNCC people have ever come to grips. And it's no shame. I mean, it is what it is. It's just your emotional system can only take so much.

02:16:18.000 --> 02:16:24.000
And I think they're hostility towards Dr. King, some of the same stuff they feel they haven't enough credit.

02:16:24.000 --> 02:16:38.000
They're operating out of those same feelings that they had at the time of all the sacrifices they and their colleagues made. Some of them were shot down right in front of them and nobody was ever, you know, penalized for it.

02:16:38.000 --> 02:16:48.000
It's like Jonathan Daniel, the guy who was in jail for eight hours. And that was very important to me too, because that was while I was there and that was not that far away from where I was.

02:16:48.000 --> 02:16:57.000
I actually had post-traumatic stress to go to Hainville. I had a real struggle going there to publicize my books for Black Belt Press.

02:16:57.000 --> 02:17:03.000
And I talked to Randy one of those one times he helped me. He said, I understand what you're going through, but it'll be good for you to go there.

02:17:03.000 --> 02:17:09.000
I said, I know they're not going to shoot me there, but they shot somebody and killed somebody there. I don't want to go there.

02:17:09.000 --> 02:17:19.000
I don't want to go there because it makes me afraid because I got shot at it. And you know what happens? I went there first person I saw was a black sheriff. I wasn't afraid anymore.

02:17:19.000 --> 02:17:24.000
If you're black people, black people were the good thing. They weren't the ones that were going to shoot me anywhere. It was the white people.

02:17:24.000 --> 02:17:36.000
When I was in jail, I had a few, I had some nation of Islam people that didn't care that I worked for Dr. King. I got some stitches in my eye from while fighting in LA County jail. That's a different story though.

02:17:36.000 --> 02:17:49.000
It was a white movement related to you. It was. When I was Dr. King's college coordinator, I was over a fair housing thing. Some black kids, Santa Monica had come and heard my music and wanted to hang out. I talked to their mom. I don't think they didn't have a dad.

02:17:49.000 --> 02:18:02.000
I was working around my place in Santa Monica in a little court. And then I got a call from, I just moved in. I got a call from the landlord who said, my wife's father just died in Italy. She's upset.

02:18:02.000 --> 02:18:08.000
Somebody called and said they were going to bomb my place because you had black people there. This was this fall of 66.

02:18:08.000 --> 02:18:17.000
I met a lot of white people in the south. Some very good Betty Adams was a woman from the Methodist Church. We had the first integrated church meeting in Macon because of Betty Adams.

02:18:17.000 --> 02:18:23.000
She said, you're working with them. When I was there for those extra three weeks, a number of interesting things happened.

02:18:23.000 --> 02:18:40.000
You asked me about the threat. Betty came. One of the good things that happened to Betty said, listen, she found me. She was the first white woman in the postal department. She was her own. She was a feminist before feminism became feminism. A lot of the men didn't like her working in post office because that was a man's job.

02:18:40.000 --> 02:18:50.000
She now raises dashhounds in the north of Macon. I've seen her. Her husband put up with all of her integration and stuff. She said, I'm working with the white Methodist youth.

02:18:50.000 --> 02:19:04.000
You're working with the black Methodist youth. Why don't we have a meeting at my house? We did. That was the first integrated meeting. Her husband, B.H. Chief Adams, good old southern boy. He let his wife do it.

02:19:04.000 --> 02:19:15.000
Because wife runs usually in marriage anyway. That was the first integrated. That was for local white women. There was a guy named Bob Brenner, who I believe is now a lay minister, was going to William & Mary. He reached out to me.

02:19:15.000 --> 02:19:24.000
Later, he had a religious house there. That summer, I met him through the church, through the Methodist church. I think he was at that meeting, actually.

02:19:24.000 --> 02:19:36.000
What happened with the threat? I was carrying the people down to vote for Marcus Moon. That night after the election, I met Dorandos office with his son Harry, who worked for the state. Harry gets a call and he said, it's for you.

02:19:36.000 --> 02:19:45.000
I was calling me at the Burrano's office. Actually, it was at our office. It was at our scope office. I think it was Bill's office to make him a gun.

02:19:45.000 --> 02:19:54.000
That's right. I think it was our scope office. I got on the phone and I could tell it was a white voice. It sounded like a nice white man. He said, are you the white man?

02:19:54.000 --> 02:20:00.000
I really liked him because I was 18 and he called me a man. I thought this was a compliment. He was going to say something nice to me.

02:20:00.000 --> 02:20:06.000
Are you the white man that was carrying the niggas down to vote today? I said yes. Then the voice changed and it wasn't nice anymore.

02:20:06.000 --> 02:20:15.000
It said, if you're still here in 24 hours, you did click. It was a very serious, it wasn't saying you're going to be better, be careful.

02:20:15.000 --> 02:20:25.000
You're here in 24 hours and you're dead. Click. I told Bill, I said, I'm not leaving. Bill said, oh yes, you're leaving tomorrow morning.

02:20:25.000 --> 02:20:32.000
I had already been scheduled to go by Dr. King's office. Everybody else drove back because I stayed and I wasn't in a SCLC field staff.

02:20:32.000 --> 02:20:41.000
I had met with Dr. King. I can tell you about that if you want and became a member of the staff. I got a check with Dr. King's signature, which was saved.

02:20:41.000 --> 02:20:49.000
It took it to the airport and got my ticket. William P. Randall was already scheduled because I had to get back to school. I had stayed three weeks extra.

02:20:49.000 --> 02:20:59.000
I was, you know, the election was over. I was time for me to go home. So I was already scheduled to go. Bill said, no, they're not going to run me out of town. He said, it's time for you to go.

02:20:59.000 --> 02:21:05.000
I'm taking you tomorrow morning. I'll be at your house. We're going. We're not discussing this.

02:21:05.000 --> 02:21:13.000
Which probably had I sobered up for a second, I would have. I mean, I wasn't, you know, but that was kind of what the movement was.

02:21:13.000 --> 02:21:18.000
I mean, I was just making you a point. Whatever. And I had been threatened a lot and I was getting to, I mean, whatever.

02:21:18.000 --> 02:21:26.000
So I got on the plane. I fell asleep. I woke up and I'm back in the way. And two nights later, I'm scared driving along me.

02:21:26.000 --> 02:21:34.000
You want to hear the Dr. King's story real quick or are you wanting to hear? Do you want me to finish the, I can tell you the real quick story of the Santa Monica.

02:21:34.000 --> 02:21:39.000
Dr. King's call. I want to just a little bit about being the coordinator. I know that's because I think it's important to me.

02:21:39.000 --> 02:21:43.000
I got to thank Dr. King. I like to tell people about thanking Dr. King because that was very special.

02:21:43.000 --> 02:21:56.000
At the end of the summer, they just called me about 40 of us. I think they probably asked probably 60 or 70 of the people they felt did well enough on their work to join the field staff and commit a year to your life.

02:21:56.000 --> 02:22:02.000
That was what it was. They came to me. He said, you've done a good job here. We need to get a lot more work to do. I want to keep scope going.

02:22:02.000 --> 02:22:10.000
I want you to commit a year to your life. Stay down with us. And I said, you know, and I want you to come on staff now. So I went on staff in America.

02:22:10.000 --> 02:22:17.000
And I said, you know, I knew my dad didn't like it too much. I didn't have parental prayers. But I was also getting a little worn out.

02:22:17.000 --> 02:22:25.000
But I also knew that I'd be classified 1A. I'd lose my student deferment. So I wasn't going to be, I don't know how I was able to, I don't know how I was able to, I was able to figure that out.

02:22:25.000 --> 02:22:35.000
And I don't know, maybe some other women didn't have that problem. And some did stay. The guys that did, I don't know how they worked that out. Maybe they had to deferment, you know, pass the deferment, whatever.

02:22:35.000 --> 02:22:41.000
But I didn't have a deferment. So I said, but I'll stay two weeks. I'll stay for the election to make it. So that was fine.

02:22:41.000 --> 02:22:53.000
So the day the project officially ended, which was August 28th, which is actually the anniversary of the I have a dream speech, that was the official date of the conclusion.

02:22:53.000 --> 02:23:03.000
We got called to that day was, those days it was West Hunter Street Baptist Church, which was Reverend Abernathy's Church. Now West Hunter Street is Martin Luther King Drive in Atlanta.

02:23:03.000 --> 02:23:16.000
So we were in the basement. And Dr. King came and Gwen Green who ran the WCLC was there and she was given flowers. Ben Clark was there, Hosea Williams was there and Dr. King was there.

02:23:16.000 --> 02:23:31.000
And he we were told that because we were now on staff, Dr. King wanted to talk to us. So he came out and he gave this wonderful speech. And Hosea Williams had all the data of how many registered voters 49,302, I think it was kept records of everything, which is in my book.

02:23:31.000 --> 02:23:40.000
And went over all of our accomplishments in the idea of the idea. Then he said, I've come out against the war. And I want you to understand it's very controversial.

02:23:40.000 --> 02:23:55.000
You're now representing our organization representing me. I want you to be able to explain to people who may ask you why I've done what I've done. Now, Dr. King came out twice against the war. He came out in 65. He actually had to retrench because there was so much criticism.

02:23:55.000 --> 02:24:07.000
And his own board was against it. He then kind of kept quiet and Coretta Scott King went around to anti-war marches and did anti-war concerts. And she was the spokesperson against the Vietnam War.

02:24:07.000 --> 02:24:15.000
He then two years later, actually the anniversary of his death, April 4, 1967 at the Riverside Church in New York, made his statement against the war.

02:24:15.000 --> 02:24:24.000
But he didn't know that he was going to have to retract at that point. At that point, he was out front. He was also up in Chicago much of that summer.

02:24:24.000 --> 02:24:36.000
So he thanked us. He explained it. And he said, are there any questions? And people have often said, you know, he also spoke to us. You know, I heard him at UCLA. I heard him at the orientation. But this was in a small group.

02:24:36.000 --> 02:24:42.000
And there were some people there. And we're in line. I got to spend a lot of time with him. I did not get to spend a lot of time with Hosea Williams.

02:24:42.000 --> 02:24:51.000
Sometime with Andy, although not that summer, really. When Andy came out to LA and Hosea Williams would come out to LA. Not never saw Dr. King in LA, but I saw Andy in Hosea Williams.

02:24:51.000 --> 02:24:56.000
So sometimes I was not in town, whatever. I was organizing him in Northern California.

02:24:56.000 --> 02:25:05.000
But so he said, are there any questions? And you know, you got 20 teenagers or a little older kind of awestruck because Martin Luther King has been thanking them.

02:25:05.000 --> 02:25:13.000
And me, you know, I worked out with Brooklyn Dodgers. I was with my heroes many time. And he was one of my heroes, but I was not awestruck enough.

02:25:13.000 --> 02:25:21.000
And I've often said, he wasn't the Martin Luther King orator. He was like Martin Luther King, the youth minister, the YMCA coordinator, just very soft spoken.

02:25:21.000 --> 02:25:32.000
Knowing I felt very strongly, I feel this now, he knew we were an awe of him. He went out of his way and knew how to make people feel comfortable. And he knew he was famous. It wasn't a big thing to him.

02:25:32.000 --> 02:25:41.000
I mean, that was just part of his job. And he made you feel comfortable. And he just seemed like this nice guy, just like he had seen me at UCLA, which I said in a program with Hosea Williams.

02:25:41.000 --> 02:25:49.000
Everybody else, because Hosea Williams was worrying, what am I going to say? We were all supposed to give memories of Dr. King on his show, The Voice of the Crusader. And he knew I didn't know Dr. King.

02:25:49.000 --> 02:25:57.000
Everybody else did. We're all the SEO veteran. And I just said, I didn't try and wing it. I mean, I don't do that. I didn't try. Well, Dr. King, I got to know him.

02:25:57.000 --> 02:26:05.000
I said, he just was a nice guy. I said, I only heard him that one time close up. And I heard me say, he seemed like he was a nice guy. Everybody else, yeah, Dr. King was really a nice guy.

02:26:05.000 --> 02:26:15.000
Because he said, you know, you think of Dr. King as a famous person. He was a person. And he took him three hours to walk from Ebenezer Baptist Church home, because he would walk home and talk to everybody along the way.

02:26:15.000 --> 02:26:25.000
Because he was a nice guy too. Tonight, he just wanted to be a nice guy. So, and Coretta Scott King was a extraordinarily nice person. I'm very fortunate to did get to know her and work with her.

02:26:25.000 --> 02:26:35.000
I'd write a letter to my father when he was ill, which was very meaningful to my father. After all, I'd been through in jail and stress. And I'm sure the stress of my being in jail when I was 19 and 20.

02:26:35.000 --> 02:26:43.000
Not good for my mom. She died a little more than a year later. That's why I went to Taylor Branch, use of the FBI documents. And I was in jail.

02:26:43.000 --> 02:26:56.000
The police chief was Peter J. Pitchess, who had been an FBI agent. And the FBI knew who I was and Marcus Crane, who said, Sirhan Sirhan was sane after he killed Robert F. Kennedy and said, I needed to be locked up in a mental hospital.

02:26:56.000 --> 02:27:10.000
Because I worked for Martin Luther King. It's extremely personal. The Taylor Branch has exploited that FBI terrible period, which the FBI has acknowledged was a terrible period. And the Congress acknowledges he had made money out of the pain that was caused by the FBI.

02:27:10.000 --> 02:27:24.000
It's very personal to Taylor. And Taylor knows that. Taylor is a coward. I've tried to talk to Taylor about it. I tried to help Taylor. And he trashed scope. And then he put it head to the nerve to put my name. And his notes saying that I helped him with his book.

02:27:24.000 --> 02:27:35.000
I helped him when he was in Selma, not knowing how to find Martin Luther King III. Because he wanted to march in the reenactment in 2005, which he had the nerve to say was risking something.

02:27:35.000 --> 02:27:52.000
It was a joke. It was protected. He said, Oh, that was dangerous to march. Taylor is great at insinuating. But I had an argument with Harris Waffer. He says, you should get off of Taylor Branch. He doesn't like Taylor. He's letting me quote him saying Taylor Branch used too much to the FBI.

02:27:52.000 --> 02:28:15.000
He didn't do much without explaining the things. I told Harris just recently. We had a argument about it because Taylor didn't put Harris's criticized Taylor Branch publicly. And he didn't put Harris's name in his new book, although he mentioned the phone call from Kennedy and Coretta Scott King, which Harris set up.

02:28:15.000 --> 02:28:27.000
And he said, America and the King years and you leave out Dr. King's friend who set up the phone call. And he said he did it for brevity. He says in a part, this is original part that he wrote for this new book. And he cut Harris's name out.

02:28:27.000 --> 02:28:42.000
And he Harris thought I was being too critical. I don't think I think it was done intentionally because Harris Taylor Branch thinks that he's so important. And he's so egotistical that he gets to decide who's in the movement. And if he doesn't put you in, you're not in.

02:28:42.000 --> 02:28:55.000
Scopes not in there either. Just like scope wasn't in eyes on the prize. Just like some of the snake people don't want to mention scope anymore. Despite the fact that many snake people worked with scope.

02:28:55.000 --> 02:29:03.000
His names are in my book in our records because they were arrested with us. And the families that hosted up, of course, were African American.

02:29:03.000 --> 02:29:17.000
So it's, and that's why Sammy Mahone has been such a great, so great to have brought Willie Bowen that in me and John R. Lewis and Willie Ricks, who said the black power thing who told me to leave Americus Willie Willie was there said white boy, we don't want you here.

02:29:17.000 --> 02:29:24.000
We want you to only value is to raise money in the North. And that was after Stokely Carmichael. It said two months earlier, we're going to sabotage scope.

02:29:24.000 --> 02:29:42.000
And some of those people are still following Stokely Carmichael's admonition from the meeting in Holly Springs, Mississippi in May of 1965, which is in their minutes, which then Ralph Featherstone, who I got to know in Berkeley at a teaching 67 who got blown up in a car in Maryland.

02:29:42.000 --> 02:29:53.000
I'm sure he didn't blow himself up, I think those explosives were planted by the government. Ralph said, let's go off record these files are in the King Center and the snake papers.

02:29:53.000 --> 02:30:04.000
He says, what do you mean sabotage Dr. King and scope? And they went off record and Ralph was against it. Stokely Carmichael said it. That's Titter branches marches orders.

02:30:04.000 --> 02:30:14.000
And Stokely Carmichael himself or Stokely Carmichael himself when he had cancer in late in his life with with Lewis Farrakhan, Louis Farrakhan in Washington.

02:30:14.000 --> 02:30:23.000
It's on video. I've not seen it, but I've heard of it. Louis Farrakhan started making negative comments about Dr. King.

02:30:23.000 --> 02:30:30.000
And when Stokely Carmichael was was in his last months of life, he said, do not say anything bad about Dr. King.

02:30:30.000 --> 02:30:40.000
He said, we attack Dr. King many, many times. This is on a video. I don't know where it is. It was filmed when they had a fundraiser for Stokely Carmichael and Washington in Louis Farrakhan was there.

02:30:40.000 --> 02:30:47.000
That's what I've been told. And he said, Dr. we attack Dr. King all those times, he never attacked us back.

02:30:47.000 --> 02:30:59.000
It finally Stokely Carmichael got the message. Willie Rick saw me at the 2007. I was late to a thing at the little tiny armory they have there at dance.

02:30:59.000 --> 02:31:09.000
And there's been many times I was the only white person there for the last couple hours. Willie noticed me. I went back and I were dancing different ones and having a good time because I was late getting there.

02:31:09.000 --> 02:31:24.000
I was outside with Willie. I had seen Willie over the years. Willie spoke at Hosea Williams's memorial service. And Terry Randolph was very close with Hosea Williams. And Willie came up to me and he said, I'm Willie Rick. I'm friends with Terry Randolph.

02:31:24.000 --> 02:31:33.000
I was friends with him. He worked with Hosea Williams. I said, I know Willie. We were down here together in 65. I said, I know who you are. I know. I know you.

02:31:33.000 --> 02:31:41.000
And I was thinking to you, Willie, it took you only took 40 years for you to want to be friends. Like 45 years. I'm glad we can be friends now.

02:31:41.000 --> 02:31:50.000
Because he told me in 65, he said, I hate all white people. He said a black state trooper in Alabama beat me up. And I hate all white people. And I said, you know, I'm really sorry that happened with a black three trooper.

02:31:50.000 --> 02:31:59.000
There's nothing to do with me. That community here is asked us here. Dr. King asked us here. Hosea Williams asked us here. And then I went in with another guy, a young guy in Dr. King staff.

02:31:59.000 --> 02:32:05.000
And we're working off stress due in 50 sit-ups at a time. And Willie watched us do in the 50 sit-ups. And then he didn't say anything else to me.

02:32:05.000 --> 02:32:12.000
But he tried to intimidate me. And you know, I mean, Willie, these white people have been shooting at me. You really can have kind of a hard time intimidating me.

02:32:12.000 --> 02:32:19.000
And there was another black guy at a meeting who told me to shut up that I didn't have a right to speak. And I said, no, I have a right to speak. I'm out in the front line.

02:32:19.000 --> 02:32:23.000
And it was usually the guy who's one in the front line to tell the white people they shouldn't be there.

02:32:23.000 --> 02:32:30.000
And you know, Willie was the guy in the flatbed truck with Hosea Williams. Willie was yelling black power on the Meredith March. And Hosea Williams was yelling freedom now.

02:32:30.000 --> 02:32:40.000
And I don't dislike, well, I'm glad Willie and I can be friends. And I'm glad that just like when Malcolm X made the pilgrimage to Mecca,

02:32:40.000 --> 02:32:46.000
and he saw that there were all different shades of Islam that he came back and it was a changed man. And was moving towards Dr. King,

02:32:46.000 --> 02:32:54.000
which Jackie Robinson writes about in his autobiography because he knew Malcolm X. And Malcolm had criticized him and was reconciling with him.

02:32:54.000 --> 02:33:04.000
And I just think that I give all the credit in the world for the snake people, for their valor and their courage. And they're in my book. Their pictures are in my book.

02:33:04.000 --> 02:33:14.000
Equally to SCLC from the King Center, the young snake group, young SCLC group. Stokely Carmichael is in there. Eldridge Cleaver is in there.

02:33:14.000 --> 02:33:24.000
That's the true history. But you know what? The true history includes the 500 of us who went south, lived with black families, as Nick wanted us to do.

02:33:24.000 --> 02:33:31.000
We said, live in the community. Don't come in and out. That was their criticism of Dr. King. So we did just what they wanted, what they did.

02:33:31.000 --> 02:33:43.000
We made roots. And some of those Nick scope organizations in a number of communities are still in existence as multimillion dollar community organizations that started during scope.

02:33:43.000 --> 02:34:02.000
And that process was something that we registered 49,203 voters, many before the Voting Rights Act of 1965. And we stood on their shoulders.

02:34:02.000 --> 02:34:19.000
They were the foundation that we followed. And that instead of resenting us, we're the same. We're together. We're part of them. And some of them are now within these books that are coming out based partly from the reunion organized.

02:34:19.000 --> 02:34:36.000
They're now embracing us. Maria Giddens book in particular about Camden, Alabama, in that county. She interviewed 26 families, many of whom were Nick, because many of the people that had been with Nick hosted the scope families and the scope volunteers.

02:34:36.000 --> 02:34:43.000
And that's what I always said. When you cut us out, you cut the families out that we lived with and the people that we marched with.

02:34:43.000 --> 02:34:56.000
And it was done out of the feeling that Dr. King got all the publicity and they didn't get their fair share. They got plenty of publicity. But I think it was more based on post-traumatic stress.

02:34:56.000 --> 02:35:11.000
Post-traumatic stress and depression is experienced in many, many, many different variations. I experienced it in my way. Believe me, anybody who went through what many of the people in the world and the freedom writers went through.

02:35:11.000 --> 02:35:23.000
Another criticism was that Dr. King didn't get on the bus in Montgomery and go the rest of the way on a freedom ride. Dr. King had three children or two children at that time. And a wife, these were single people. I was single.

02:35:23.000 --> 02:35:35.000
Easier for us to put our lives on the line. We don't have children. We don't have wives. And they criticize them for that. You know what? Time to get over it.

02:35:35.000 --> 02:35:49.000
It's history. I make no criticism for anything that was done at that time because when people have their lives on the line that are years of stress, people used to go to Atlanta for R&R and they self-medicated, they would go out and drink.

02:35:49.000 --> 02:36:04.000
It's what soldiers do. That's what soldiers do because of the fear of the stress. That's okay. That's why I wanted to tell Frank Smith Jr in Washington when he told me, we were first words out of us. We weren't tougher than Dr. King. When I told him about the son of the bitch thing.

02:36:04.000 --> 02:36:14.000
No, you were as tough. You didn't have a bulls eye on you every day that Dr. King had every day until one day he got him. He knew that. He knew that.

02:36:14.000 --> 02:36:29.000
He'd Harris-Waffer talks about that. That his wife, Coretta Scott King, talked about that in 56. And he went out every day without any protection. That's pretty good. That's pretty amazing. He deserved, he was the leader.

02:36:29.000 --> 02:36:45.000
That doesn't mean that Frank Smith Jr wasn't the leader, that Kwame Ture and Stokeley were leaders too. They were great leaders. He was the main leader. He had it all. He had the education, he had the oratory, he had the courage, he had the humanity.

02:36:45.000 --> 02:36:55.000
He was an African American. He was proud of him. He was part of you. You were part of him. In the same old scope.

02:36:55.000 --> 02:37:05.000
The people I don't like are the David Garros and the Taylor branches. Taylor was not involved. He claimed he sat in a jail so he was arrested. He never went behind bars.

02:37:05.000 --> 02:37:17.000
He wanted to be like, I heard him on the radio. He wanted to be Stokely Carmichael Carmichael so I got a black card game. Then he got picked up by the sheriff. He didn't want him to get in trouble. Then he sat in the jail and he showed his yellow ID.

02:37:17.000 --> 02:37:33.000
He went off to his motel. 1969. Not part of the era. But he was trying to build his resume. That's what the guy is about. I'm telling you this because I know the guy. I dealt with him enough so I don't talk about it. He said this to his face. I said it in Birmingham at a meeting when he was at the Civil Rights Institute.

02:37:33.000 --> 02:37:41.000
I don't talk about people. Some people didn't like it. I said it there. Harris has also said it much nicer than me. I'm about using the FBI stuff.

02:37:41.000 --> 02:37:51.000
Anyway, if you want to ask a question about being the college coordinator, I can give that real quick. I would like to talk about the 21st of the 21st.

02:37:51.000 --> 02:38:05.000
I appreciate that. I appreciate that. Unfortunately, this history of scope has been left out. The reason is why I think it's worth talking about.

02:38:05.000 --> 02:38:20.000
Sammy Mahone is the model. He was a snake leader in America. He's a leader. He's had us both there. He did it before I said it. I'm following Sammy's lead. He's embracing everybody and being inclusive.

02:38:20.000 --> 02:38:29.000
It's time we do that. That's the true story. That involves more black people than white people. Taylor is right about that. It was a tiny number of Jews, a tiny number of others.

02:38:29.000 --> 02:38:41.000
Percentage-wise, we are a tiny group. The whites. Even in the black community, although it's a pretty significant part of the black community was involved one way or another. Not everybody. Not everybody.

02:38:41.000 --> 02:38:47.000
Even then, you were taking big risks. You want to ask questions about being the college coordinator.

02:38:47.000 --> 02:38:50.000
Maybe just one last thing that you want to say.

02:38:50.000 --> 02:38:56.000
The college coordinator was, I got back. I walked into the meeting and Gwen Green, who was a leader, said,

02:38:56.000 --> 02:39:01.000
because I came back late because I had been in the South. I went to the first meeting. I got there late. She said,

02:39:01.000 --> 02:39:07.000
our leader is here. Our coordinator is here. I literally looked behind me to see what she was talking about.

02:39:07.000 --> 02:39:14.000
I think what happened was when I raised my hand and talked to Dr. King. Hannah was there and talked it over. They decided that I would be the college coordinator.

02:39:14.000 --> 02:39:23.000
I protested that I was the youngest one. Gwen said, no, you've been selected. I later asked her many years, why did I get to see her? We knew you would do a good job. We saw you did good work.

02:39:23.000 --> 02:39:33.000
I organized a conference. The real thing was, the scope was kind of ending. Black Power was starting. Hannah War Movement was starting. It was very hard to recruit.

02:39:33.000 --> 02:39:41.000
Dr. King only had one reach, two regional offices. One in DC was a lobbying office at Rev. Walter Fauntroy, Rand. One was the Western Christian Leadership Conference,

02:39:41.000 --> 02:39:49.000
Southerner Christian Leadership Conference, Rev. Thomas Kilgore Jr, who had been in New York, was now out here. He was the president.

02:39:49.000 --> 02:39:59.000
These ministers around the country that Dr. King had organized back in 57 as the SCLC. Some at least Kilgore had come from, Reverend Kilgore had come from New York out here.

02:39:59.000 --> 02:40:11.000
I don't know where he was in 57, but he had been a long-term guy. We did the conference. We did Operation Breadbasket, where we went when Jesse Jackson was starting in Chicago.

02:40:11.000 --> 02:40:23.000
We started there, apparently. I was not quite as charismatic as Jesse. He had more SCLC troops there. We did evaluations and we got jobs.

02:40:23.000 --> 02:40:28.000
We did exactly the same thing. Went around to the stores in the black areas. How many employees do you have?

02:40:28.000 --> 02:40:38.000
Worked with the churches. That was a WACLC scope, SCLC kind of thing out here. But when Andy and Hosea Williams would come out periodically,

02:40:38.000 --> 02:40:50.000
when would call me down there at 2401 Southwestern Avenue. I think, two, I think it is, it's in the book.

02:40:50.000 --> 02:40:54.000
That's what we get that address right.

02:40:56.000 --> 02:41:08.000
2400, 2400 Southwestern Avenue, Suite 102, Los Angeles, California, I know 018. It was Thomas Kilgore, was the director Western Bureau SCLC, which was essentially W.

02:41:08.000 --> 02:41:14.000
Then we had Marvin T. Robert, Marvin T. Robert, Marvin T. Robert, Marvin T. Robert, the president of W.C.L.C.

02:41:14.000 --> 02:41:22.000
Robert, Marvin Stovall, chairman of the board W. So they had their own board. It was Western Christian leaders from Congress, Mountain Earth, the King, Jr. Founder.

02:41:22.000 --> 02:41:31.000
It was sort of a separate board. It was Washington, Oregon, California, Nevada, Arizona, Colorado, and Mexico, Utah, Alaska, and Hawaii.

02:41:31.000 --> 02:41:37.000
When Green was the director of the director, she since told me that all the male ministers didn't make it that she had to fight as a woman.

02:41:37.000 --> 02:41:44.000
But she was the executive director. She was a woman in the leadership. She was on the payroll. I think she was probably the only one on the payroll.

02:41:44.000 --> 02:41:50.000
She had a labor background. She later worked for Councilman Bob Farrell, still alive, still in LA.

02:41:51.000 --> 02:42:03.000
That's a great history for that neighborhood. I hope someday we're going to get a marker there. Let those schools in that area know that the ministers in that area know that they're part of the Martin Luther King legacy directly.

02:42:03.000 --> 02:42:11.000
Dr. King went to that when he spoke of the sports arena, not long before he died, I'm sure he was at W.C.L.C.

02:42:11.000 --> 02:42:23.000
And then so I did a number of things. I organized a little bit up in Berkeley. I had James Bevel come out. I had this incident where the kids in my neighborhood, these three black kids came over. They were like 10, 8, and 6.

02:42:23.000 --> 02:42:32.000
I talked to their mom as it okay if they visit. A landlord said, you know, I want you to move. I said it's against the law to make a threat.

02:42:32.000 --> 02:42:41.000
But I had told all these white people I talked about Betty Adam. But the main thing, the white people that didn't want to shoot me came up and particularly in making, not in America. They didn't talk to you in America.

02:42:41.000 --> 02:42:47.000
They shot at you. But in making, they would talk to me. They'd say, you're a hypocrite. What have you done? Isn't there any problems back in LA?

02:42:47.000 --> 02:42:53.000
And of course, once the Watts situation happened when I was at a coin in the air at the time, I thought, these white people here might have a point.

02:42:53.000 --> 02:43:03.000
We might have some problems in California. And that was another reason why I told Hosea Williams I can't stay. I've got work to do where I live. And that's so I ended up doing work here.

02:43:03.000 --> 02:43:17.000
And so, you know, so that stuff was going on. And I organized a little bit up in Northern California.

02:43:17.000 --> 02:43:28.000
You know, the organization was a big organization. I didn't do anything. I was essentially the Western States college coordinator. But I was only doing things in Northern Southern California.

02:43:28.000 --> 02:43:46.000
And then, but because, so I would know Andy and Hosea Williams, that was a key thing. The other thing was because of being on the staff, when Dr. King made his appeal about Resurrection City three years later, he didn't appeal that he wrote for look magazine before he died.

02:43:46.000 --> 02:43:58.000
That came out after he died April 4th that said we need volunteers to go to demonstrate. We've had all these summers of violence in the in the black sections around the country.

02:43:58.000 --> 02:44:12.000
We need to channel this into a non violent way in Washington at the poor people's campaign. And I felt that was worth me going. My dad was very against it. I had been in jail. I dropped out of school. I just gotten back in school.

02:44:12.000 --> 02:44:25.000
And he didn't want me to go. In fact, he told me if you go this time, I'm cutting you off. Well, he hadn't given me any money since when I was out of school. And he hadn't given me any, give me $100 for the, my dad thought it was like when the tuition wasn't the 50s.

02:44:25.000 --> 02:44:41.000
So, I, you know, and he was pretty serious. And I understood why my mom at that point was ill. They were divorced, but she was, you know, she died that fall. It was a lot of stress for my family. It's another reason why I resent people who weren't there like Taylor Branch or David Garrow cutting out those of us.

02:44:41.000 --> 02:44:58.000
It wasn't just me who's my family shared that experience. It was hard on them. My family never ever, many of my cousins don't understand, they haven't understood it. The post-traumatic stress I had, they haven't understood. They never even asked me what happened. The Jewish community has never asked me until it had been a breath last year.

02:44:58.000 --> 02:45:18.000
You know, this is a big deal in my life and a big deal in my family's life. I never worried about it not being written about, but when Taylor Branch and David Garrow went out of their way to trash us and disrespect our work and falsify our work with fake documents. That was a little too much for me.

02:45:18.000 --> 02:45:26.000
For somebody like Taylor Branch is my age who was having a comfortable summer in Atlanta when I was down getting shot at.

02:45:26.000 --> 02:45:42.000
Walk the walk if you want to talk about that. Willie Ricks, Rick's Walk the Walk. I'll discuss that with them without a problem. I don't hold it against them. I think we need to bond and be a team together as we were in many places anyway.

02:45:42.000 --> 02:45:57.000
Anyway, with these kids, they were there, turned out the landlord was an ex-sendom on a policeman, which I didn't know at the time. When I went down there, they said, we're not going to do anything. I said, I need somebody to come and take a report.

02:45:57.000 --> 02:46:08.000
So we're not going to take a report. Because the landlord told them I wasn't telling the truth and he was an ex-cop. I was really worried because I told you, when I came out, I said, I'm not putting up with this anymore.

02:46:08.000 --> 02:46:22.000
I really didn't know. I went and saw my rabbi who had paid my way for me and four other Jewish students from UCLA. He said, guns are okay. He knew about Israel of independence or whatever. He said, if you need protection at your house, you need protection at your house.

02:46:22.000 --> 02:46:28.000
The first thing you need to do is find out whether there was really a threat. You better call the landlord and see if he's telling the truth.

02:46:28.000 --> 02:46:34.000
Well, that was a discussion after Friday night services by a time the cold landlord was maybe 930-10 at night on a Friday night.

02:46:34.000 --> 02:46:45.000
And I had bought a gun. The police told me, if you want any protection by a gun, that's when I asked the rabbi. And I bought a gun. I said, can I have a gun? They said, you can have a shotgun if you're over 18.

02:46:45.000 --> 02:46:52.000
I went down and bought a shotgun. I mean, I'd been through again. This was the real deal to me. I mean, I'd been through it. I wasn't about to have that happen again.

02:46:52.000 --> 02:46:58.000
Not Dr. King would have been happy about it. I'm not sure that Hosea Williams would have cared. So I had the shotgun. I didn't want anything happen.

02:46:58.000 --> 02:47:05.000
I talked to the rabbi, I called the landlord and I said, look, please told me to buy. I didn't know he was next cop at the time. I'll find that out later.

02:47:05.000 --> 02:47:13.000
So I didn't know, I said, I don't know, I want to know if this is true. I've talked to my rabbi. The police told me to buy a gun. I'm worried somebody might bomb my place.

02:47:13.000 --> 02:47:24.000
That's what you told me. Is that true? Were you making that up? Or was it true? He hung up at me, called the police, told him that I was threatening people with a shotgun. That's not a good thing.

02:47:24.000 --> 02:47:32.000
They came down with a city attorney named Herbert Lapine. I'd love to get his name in because he told my dad he was going to put me in jail for life.

02:47:32.000 --> 02:47:45.000
I had a gun, because I had the gun with me. I didn't have a phone yet. I went down to the corner at Santa Monica in 26th Street. Call from a phone booth.

02:47:45.000 --> 02:47:53.000
I was walking back. I had had taken self-defense from a guy named Brick's Hunt. He was the wrestling coach and an Olympic wrestling coach and a drill instructor from World War II.

02:47:53.000 --> 02:48:01.000
Once I knew I was going to go, I took self-defense and I paid attention when they taught about guns. I had the gun open, but it was loaded.

02:48:01.000 --> 02:48:12.000
I was walking back. I came in my alley and there were two policemen from Santa Monica with guns up. They said, drop the gun. I said it's broken open. I can't be fired. Herbert Lapine, the city attorney, was there.

02:48:12.000 --> 02:48:28.000
They said, you have three. Drop the gun. I said, it can't be dropped. They said, two. I dropped the gun. They would have killed me. Just like you read about all the black panthers I got, I would have become almost a sympathetic black panther in a sense that I wasn't going to take it anymore.

02:48:28.000 --> 02:48:37.000
Deacon defense, that's where I was. Not a good place to be. That's where I was. Drop the gun. They took it. I said, okay, you're here now. Will you take the report about the bomb threat?

02:48:37.000 --> 02:48:53.000
No, we don't think you're stable enough for the gun. We're taking the gun. I at that point wasn't experiencing post-traumatic stress, but I had had a depression. By that point I was feeling fine. I was in really good shape. I had built fences for my alcohol all summer. I was in great shape.

02:48:53.000 --> 02:49:13.000
They took the gun. They wouldn't take a report. I went back down there, followed him down on my motorcycle. Not again a good idea. I was 19. I said, I want you to take the report. They said, get the hell out of here. We're going to beat the shit out here. Put you in jail. Get out here. This was before Tom Hayden and Jane Fonda socialized Santa Monica. It was a different town back then.

02:49:13.000 --> 02:49:28.000
This is fall 66. One back home, two days later, it had been three days. I called from a phone booth. I said, look at it. It's three days. I'm calm down. I told myself, I still keep taking it. I want a property receipt. It wouldn't even give me a property receipt.

02:49:28.000 --> 02:49:34.000
Essentially, they stole my gun. I couldn't be a very good black Panther without my gun. I'm joking about the black. I didn't use that terminology.

02:49:34.000 --> 02:49:44.000
I was doing what later people did when they got frustrated with injustice and brutality. I was at the same phone booth and they said, okay, we'll bring where are you? I told them I had the phone booth. We'll bring it down to you.

02:49:44.000 --> 02:49:59.000
The cop car comes down. The guy jumped out and I'm in the thing. I said, oh, you brought my gun. They said, no, you're under arrest. Again, in the phone booth. I can just out. It's what Bob Zellner calls up north. I said, what a matter of arrest for? They said, you're disturbing the piece. I said, you're not going to make that sick. I'm in the phone booth.

02:49:59.000 --> 02:50:06.000
They said, I'll make it sick. The guy grabbed me and twisted my arm and started pulling me to the car. I said, take your fucking hands off me. I said, you can arrest me but don't touch me.

02:50:06.000 --> 02:50:18.000
So then he came at me and I went in the car. That's when I told him, we're going to the station. I said, when you got on this car, I said, don't touch me. I said, you can put me in jail. Do not touch me.

02:50:18.000 --> 02:50:29.000
He said, if I have to use my ability, he said, I'm going to do what I have to do. If I have to hit you, I said, do you have to use your ability?

02:50:29.000 --> 02:50:41.000
I have to use my fucking. This was what was going on in my mind. We got out of the car right behind the book in the parking room. The parking station is still there right off the freeway.

02:50:41.000 --> 02:50:56.000
He came at me and I, like I said, was a very good shape. I had self defense. I knocked him down and jumped on him. I did learn and the jail psychiatrist later told me, that is not a good thing to do. He hit a policeman outside a booking room at a police station.

02:50:56.000 --> 02:51:03.000
I was on top of him and then four police, they came out of the station pretty quickly when they hear that's going on, when their officers is down.

02:51:03.000 --> 02:51:12.000
And four officers, each grab, each one grab legs and arms and pulled me off, threw me over and bang my head on the ground until I passed out.

02:51:12.000 --> 02:51:19.000
I told them, once they had me spread eagle, I was stopping. I said, okay, they kept smashing my head on the ground until I passed them.

02:51:19.000 --> 02:51:29.000
They broke me in and they punched me around. Then they said, I said, okay, you got me here? You got me for disturbing the piece? I'm going to sue you.

02:51:29.000 --> 02:51:36.000
Another nut could really sell him that later. They said, well, you know what? You promised to move out of town and let you go.

02:51:36.000 --> 02:51:45.000
That's when I should have said, yes. Again, 19 years old, I said, no, I'm going to sue you. I said, I'm a civil rights worker, I'm going to sue you.

02:51:45.000 --> 02:51:53.000
They put me in jail and they charged me instead of disturbing the piece, they charged me with a 653 MAPC of the penal code.

02:51:53.000 --> 02:52:02.000
I'm not sure that it exists anymore. It's a threatening or obscene phone call. They said that I threatened them over the phone, that I threatened the police department over the phone.

02:52:02.000 --> 02:52:12.000
Nobody can prove what anybody says unless they have an untamed. They never thought I was ever going to have to go to trial and they dropped charges from that chain.

02:52:12.000 --> 02:52:23.000
They put what they call a department 95, which is a psychiatric hold, which is then a pathway to institutionalization commitment. That's what they tried to do.

02:52:23.000 --> 02:52:32.000
What happened was they sent me to a guy named Ronald Markman, who still alive became a very famous jail psychiatrist and wrote in a book, a UCLA in his own Westwood.

02:52:32.000 --> 02:52:40.000
He saw me and he was a cool guy. He was in his 30s at the time and he said, what are you doing here? You're a UCLA student. I said, well, this is what happened. He said, okay.

02:52:40.000 --> 02:52:50.000
He said, you're not crazy. I'm going to give you a clearance. My parents couldn't bail me out. We got a department 95. You can't even get bail. My parents are going to bail me out. They couldn't get me out.

02:52:50.000 --> 02:53:05.000
He said, I'm going to get bailed out. I said, I'm telling you two things. I said, you're probably going to want to protest the Vietnam or I'm going to tell you never hit a cop and particularly never at a booking room.

02:53:05.000 --> 02:53:16.000
He said, okay, you're okay. I got bailed out and I couldn't live in the place. I went to stay with my girlfriend and something happened with her and my ex roommate, Guy, from the club, UCLA came by.

02:53:16.000 --> 02:53:29.000
I got an argument with him. He called the police. He told them that I was out on bail on the other. They arrested me for battery, which was bogus, but the two city attorneys got together.

02:53:29.000 --> 02:53:43.000
They then held me in jail 112 days. I called Hosea Williams. I tried to get to Atlanta. I got kicked off the Delta airline plane. Hosea Williams said, come down here. We can't do anything for you there. I said, the media won't take the story. Come down here and I actually got kicked off the plane. They sent me back.

02:53:43.000 --> 02:53:49.000
They told me I worked for Martin Luther King. Not the same Delta Airlines either. I told the students, I worked for Martin Luther King and they kicked me off the plane.

02:53:49.000 --> 02:53:55.000
I just likened the Jackie Robinson movie. They kicked me off the plane. They happened to me. I have a little intersection with the Jackie Robinson.

02:53:55.000 --> 02:54:07.000
Anyway, make the long story short. Immediately when they found out my mother was a professor at USC. My father was a prominent chiropractor. He was the national public relations chair for the National Care Chiropractic Association.

02:54:07.000 --> 02:54:19.000
I've been on the Today Show. It was very prominent at that time. They offered me a deal. We'll drop charge. You signed a stipulation of probable cause. You can't sue us. We'll drop the threatening phone call charge.

02:54:19.000 --> 02:54:32.000
I wouldn't do it, which pissed my dad off. Then they brought me to trial to the other one. The city attorney came down and lied to me and said, witnesses were going to be there that weren't there.

02:54:32.000 --> 02:54:43.000
I got convicted by a judge. A guy named Woodman Z was a liberal judge of Mr. Meanor Battery and Distoring the Peace. They then put me up for another department 95.

02:54:43.000 --> 02:54:51.000
In the jail at that time, they had one chief jail psychiatrist. That was Marcus Crane. He was a colleague of Peter J. Pitchess. He was a colleague of J. Edgar Hoover.

02:54:51.000 --> 02:55:01.000
Marcus Crane wrote a terrible report. They told me about me. The same guy that two years later said Sirhan was not sick for killing. He was completely sane when he killed Bobby Kennedy.

02:55:01.000 --> 02:55:10.000
I thought that was interesting. I was sick for having attacked a policeman who had defended myself against a policeman, but Sirhan was not sick for killing.

02:55:10.000 --> 02:55:19.000
Finally, I kept or went back to Markman. He said, what are you doing here again? I said, well, I got arrested again. They messing with me.

02:55:19.000 --> 02:55:28.000
I'm going to certify you again, but he said, you got to start being careful here. You're getting arrested too much. Then they took me to court and they said, we want to send him back again.

02:55:28.000 --> 02:55:35.000
They wouldn't try me on the second charge. On the first charge. They sent me to all the jail psychiatrists. They had ten of them.

02:55:35.000 --> 02:55:45.000
When I got to the eighth one, he told me, they had to have two. They had to have Crane, the head guy and one other one, then they could put me up for commitment. They would never have to try me for the criminal charge.

02:55:45.000 --> 02:56:00.000
They started telling me, the last couple of psychiatrists, they told me, they said, we know Dr. Markman. We've seen this report. They talked to me. They said, you're not crazy. They said, but you better be careful. They are trying to put you away and throw away the key.

02:56:00.000 --> 02:56:08.000
You are in trouble now. You've got to start being more careful and take this more seriously and not get arrested again when you get out.

02:56:08.000 --> 02:56:18.000
Finally, they could never get the second guy. They finally had, and they kept taking continuances on the threatening phone call.

02:56:18.000 --> 02:56:30.000
When I went to court after the third continuance, Herbert Lapine said to my dad, I'm going to put him away for life. That's when my dad said over my dead body.

02:56:30.000 --> 02:56:44.000
He was trying to pique a chiropractor and lead her in his field. He had been a long struggle after World War II out of the projects. He was just remarried doing well. Here's his son in all this stuff.

02:56:44.000 --> 02:56:53.000
Finally, I go back to court on the sentencing for the battery and they say, we're going to let you out, but you have to be committed.

02:56:53.000 --> 02:57:03.000
I said, I'm not going to be committed. I just went to your psychiatrist and eight out of nine or nine out of ten. They sent me to ten. Nine out of ten said, they don't need to be committed. Why would I want to commit myself?

02:57:03.000 --> 02:57:21.000
Then Judge Woodman said, okay, six months in jail. I had already been in two months back to jail. But at that time, I didn't cause any trouble in jail. Before I flooded the jail, I had stopped a black Muslim nation of Islam guy beating up a Hispanic guy, which he then later put him in the same cell block.

02:57:21.000 --> 02:57:34.000
He hit me with a bar soap with a razor blade and cut my eye. I tried to actually was trying to kill me. He kicked me in the head with his boots. The funny part of that was there was quite a bit of blood. And when they took me in to sew me up, some of the deputies came in.

02:57:34.000 --> 02:57:41.000
Then kind of liked me because they thought it was kind of tough. And I wasn't causing too many more problems because I had decided I would go back to jail instead of going to a mental hospital.

02:57:41.000 --> 02:57:59.000
So they said, love and thought we knew somebody was going to get you. And I think he was put up to it by then. And I said, well, they said, we knew somebody's going to get you. I said, well, they said, yeah, I busted open your eye. I said, well, I know I got a few on him. And they said, he was this guy with his name was Hugo Maxi. He was on parole, from from solid. He was a tough guy.

02:57:59.000 --> 02:58:09.000
When I got down he kicked me I threw him over me, which I learned from Big Sun. Got up and kicked me in the head with big boots. And that's when I realized this is not a regular fight. This guy is trying to kill me.

02:58:09.000 --> 02:58:24.000
So I got up and I defended myself. How's on my feet when it ended? So they said, I said, well, I know I got a few on with him. Didn't he have some injuries? And they said, the only thing we noticed with Hugo Maxi, some of his knuckles were bruised. That seemed to be the only damage he did with him.

02:58:24.000 --> 02:58:39.000
So what happened was to finish it out. I go back to court. So then they hear that, so I finally got to go back to court on the original charge of disturbing the piece. This is now three and a half months later or two hundred and twelve days later.

02:58:39.000 --> 02:58:50.000
And they have no more psychiatrist to send me to. They've run out. They can't do the department 95. So they make a deal with the judge with men's Z.

02:58:50.000 --> 02:58:58.000
